10	Terrebonne Bay	3		\nTHE DEEP EVENING-COLORED ROSE of the sea\r is closing. Sweet crude oil, orange as rust,\r finds an open pathway into the marsh.\r And what you thought would be your home,\r lush with grasses, is no home, drives you out into the gray-glazed\r gates of sleep. Blood flowers\r where we don’t see it. And every chance event\r is a high note racing from stars in sea-depths of brightness,\r and every shock we feel we feel only with the slack\r ropes of our arms. Someone\r wants to hide the body of oil and cannot.\r Someone wants to hide their hands from shame.\r Shark, dolphin, manatee, fish,\r each slick skin an undreamt tine threading its red\r flute-dusk through fumes.\r Sound of the flood-dark pulse.\r Then the second when the water makes no sound.\r  \r  \r THE OLD VANDALS WERE FLOODS AND BOATS\r eroding the banks. The islands that once dotted the bays\r have sunk, disappearing into silverish grit, thinned\r into algae and filament now being made\r quiet by plumes. Despite ourselves\r we are made quiet. The death of the sea\r a thing we must lower ourselves into\r to imagine. I will stay with you here\r inside the sheen of orange that quickly kills,\r not like the saltwater slowly starving the freshwater-\r marshes and grasses that knit this green-wet\r world together. The two breathless gannets\r found covered in oil are not unlike you,\r at the mercy of a mercy that moves in plumes,\r that insists certain fates remain\r invisible. What existed before the oil arrived\r was delicate and mired, a broom of moonlight\r swept through half-choked waves. I trust you\r if you wish for what it, too, might have been.\r  \r  \r LEADING INTO THE BAY are soft green expanses of\r grasses, saltwater channels, slicks\r not glimpsed here before.\r The birds bathe where they can,\r in half-damp shadows that make possible the next free\r climb into air. There is nothing beyond our means to feel it—\r oil pushing up to the surface where the surface-dwellers die,\r turtles pulling in from the Gulf for nesting.\r If I close my eyes I can hear the faint blue\r traces of blood over-gathered by oil\r and the sound of ice near the seafloor.\r  \r There will be a time when nothing living moves,\r a degradation of stillness beyond any liquid scar.\r Still, the solutions of despair are weak\r if you believe you can touch an undersea reef,\r the belly of a small wounded whale.\r You have the power to feel it.\r The breath of the animal\r moving like trust into your arms.\r  \r  \r BEFORE THE HOUR WHEN THE COAST slid into ocean\r we thought we saw a patch of sun greening in waves.\r The slip of a fish. There was a need\r so deep in our bodies we could not even weep.\r We called for an end and that end\r did not come. Power after power, our machine tools\r and cutting tools did nothing to hold back the brown clouds\r rippling in chaotic columns toward the light.\r And what the skies mean, passing over beds of tarred\r seaweed, feels unutterable, like the darkness\r around a candle. Where had we hoped to live?\r You came into the month with dreams.\r You walked on those beaches even though\r you knew they were sick. The bird that sought\r the reeds to die in, the fish gill-soaked with oils—\r you gathered them into yourself as if you alone\r could bring back their flickering.\r And overhead the novae exploded toward you\r along tracks of gas and dust, and the fields of ocean\r rose into you, and the crabs broke from their cancer fossils\r in masses of tiny flowers and you felt inside you\r the islands re-arise, flushed from the thickening\r imbalance of the earth. (Is there some\r refuge beyond ourselves that is vast enough?\r The sea is without grief. As are the days.)\n	'air':328 'alga':169 'alon':585 'along':598 'anim':436 'aris':634 'arm':91,442 'around':533 'arriv':264 'back':506,588 'bank':153 'bath':311 'bay':2,160,295 'beach':553 'bed':524 'believ':411 'belli':419 'beyond':332,398,647 'bird':310,562 'blood':52,371 'blue':368 'boat