11	Variations on a Trance	3		\nRobins in the cottonwoods,\r holding still as the thin snow comes.\r The sun seems to flood them with blood.\r They have settled in the empty branches\r while the storm-lamps spit in your limbs,\r red evening swinging across the sky then dropping,\r ragged, into your frame to stay with you\r as you move and smile and have opinions.\r Then a woman’s torso white with dawn—\r their rich perch is yours, there is nothing you need\r to expect or retrieve, like warm fields\r floating toward an invisible moon.\r A person learns stone-throated composures\r and barters for days of calm weather,\r like a man in a dream who understands the answering\r pressure of eyes—you ask too much.\r But the birds are not reckless.\r Every minute their fat shapes are filling with sun,\r and I apprentice myself to their candor.\r Their bodies drift on the moving branches, solid—\r they are not taking and keeping.\r They are not torn papers in a rumor of wind,\r their small backs brown fields holding thunderclouds up.\r Inside their bodies, nothing falls to the earth and dies.\n	'across':43 'answer':117 'apprentic':142 'ask':122 'back':173 'barter':102 'bird':127 'blood':23 'bodi':148,181 'branch':30,153 'brown':174 'calm':106 'candor':146 'come':15 'composur':100 'cottonwood':8 'dawn':71 'day':104 'die':188 'dream':113 'drift':149 'drop':47 'earth':186 'empti':29 'even':41 'everi':131 'expect':83 'eye':120 'fall':183 'fat':134 'field':88,175 'fill':137 'float':89 'flood':20 'frame':51 'hold':9,176 'insid':179 'invis':92 'keep':160 'lamp':35 'learn':96 'like':86,108 'limb':39 'man':110 'minut':132 'moon':93 'move':58,152 'much':124 'need':81 'noth':79,182 'opinion':63 'paper':165 'perch':74 'person':95 'pressur':118 'rag':48 'reckless':130 'red':40 'retriev':85 'rich':73 'robin':5 'rumor':168 'seem':18 'settl':26 'shape':135 'sky':45 'small':172 'smile':60 'snow':14 'solid':154 'spit':36 'stay':53 'still':10 'stone':98 'stone-thro':97 'storm':34 'storm-lamp':33 