21	Scorpio, or, The Scorpion	6		\nNow as the farmer sits at his accounts\r Reviewing fleeces neath deciduous beeches\r And notes in red contented ink\r Net profits of his quite impossible serenity;\r As graded apples marketably beautiful\r Into the bushel-baskets sink\r And trussed hay to the tin roof reaches,\r And where red tiles through darkening trees are reared\r A whole year's work is sold in sacks of meal;\r Now suddenly running\r Drops like a sprig\r Of oak in a gale on the neck\r The little wriggler,\r Vindictive-legged cunning,\r Drops like a fleck\r Of blood on a finger ring\r Crooking in his sting.\r It wriggles and stops,\r Wriggles and turns\r Through copper ferns\r Through stubble of crops\r Into the garden of his most impossible serenity.\r Chrysanthemums\r Wilt in alarm\r As dangerous comes\r Its arching arm\r A probable harm\r Nearer to his impossible serenity.\r Brambles turn sour\r Berries crinkle\r All fruits,\r Every flower,\r All roots wrinkle:\r The trees' atour\r Lapses, and the power\r Of his impossible serenity\r Collapses.\r The scorpion poison grips, its patterns spread\r Like wine that trickling on a dusty floor\r Hence and thence makes pellets and canals.\r Asphodel, improbable, beside the river bed\r Is found rank ramsons with a garlic smell.\r And cider in a dirty cask, lovelike, turns vinegar.\r Where had been pears and pippins, is a row of rotten balls,\r Globes of mundungus, faced with foul fungus,\r And locusts swarm to make the end complete.\r The last bee disembowelled waves its dislocated feet.\r Diseased the last elm falls, and with it falls\r The indistinct last glint of Dionysus\r Lysius.\r Earth is with scorpions like spiders hung.\r From every tile and brick they flick\r Like leaping twisting mixing flies on dung.\r A pretty virgin makes a pretty shrew,\r As those lo longer virgins also do,\r Because they are no longer so, or else because they are.\r The fracasado, self-considering as from far,\r By force of self-perverted scales\r Pities himself for impotence, and rails\r Oftener therefore: more he pities, more he fails.\r The scolding wife drives man to keep a scolding whore:\r If either dies, he grieves because she scolds no more,\r And scorns the other still because she scolds.\r The man whose one wife makes him ten cuckolds\r Wishes the girl were plain: she finds no joys\r In playing with her multiplicated boys,\r Wishes herself plain too, to find her joy in one. Whose wife\r Is dutiful and bashful all her life\r Thinks he would be happier if she were loved by other men.\r Surely some wit usurps the throne of Cypris, when\r Woman so seems what never woman was,\r For man to caper to as man should not.\r The golden mean is not.\r The man of business bonded to his trade\r Postpones his culture till his fortune has been made.\r The cultured man to realize his will\r Can find no means, nor wherewithal to touch\r His learning, since his culture costs too much.\r Reformers, visionaries, poets, other such,\r Because their vision real is, too sane their wit,\r The multitude they seek to benefit\r Lunatic calls them: and although they spurn\r Others' opinions, lunatic for lack of heed they turn,\r Parodying their visions of perfection.\r The land, too stupid to desire a change,\r Too lazy for that mental insurrection,\r Yet knowing their salvation lies\r In broader education\r Like cats enough uneasy to surmise\r They have the mange,\r Further enlightenment refuses\r And its chief men accuses\r Of unenlightenment,\r With consequent\r Stagnation.\r Over its losses\r Autumn its mosses\r Draws: the dormice go to sleep.\r In the shorter afternoons\r Determined to forget, the caterpillars crawl\r Into the weak oblivion of cocoons.\r To easier life the coward birds have all\r Flown from the towns and woods and pools:\r But some remain at large, poor ignorant fools.\r The bats are wiser, who hang upside down,\r Less crazily inverted than the town:\r Snails in cement immure their sleepy souls:\r Less mad, though timid, are the celibate\r Ferns that abide the next arriving spring\r To unroll fronds again, when warblers sing,\r Meantime intelligently hibernate,\r And delicately,\r Up to date.\r But we as leaves evacuate a lime\r Cannot deceive ourselves nor bide our time:\r Forced to retire by buds that seize our place,\r Self-superannuated, in disgrace,\r Know but too well that what we most deride\r In others is the poison on our side,\r Stung by the poison we ourselves put up\r Ourselves the poisoned cup\r We give our intellectual pride\r To sup.\r A scorpion drops from a unicorn's nape\r Into the virgin's lap.\r A scorpion drops from blood Xanthippê's tongue\r And Socratês though he have wrung\r A whole night's liquor from a score kulixes\r And sadly his wine mixes,\r Drinking all below the table,\r Wanders, constitutionally unable\r To drink himself unwise.\r Yes, even him approaching now to weigh these things\r The scorpion stings.\r This belt of fretted stars that so promiscuously plays\r Upon our eyes, we learn to name them all,\r Picking our favourites out like horses in a race.\r But now their steady passages recall\r How, geared to the years,\r They tick our lives out: and we cease to see\r Much hope in false futurity:\r Instead we falsify stars that have been\r With promise that we alter since those stars,\r Raising reality\r Not in what we see,\r Nor in what meteors there yet may be,\r But in fixed stars we would we once had seen.\r  \n	'abid':662 'account':12 'accus':574 'afternoon':595 'alarm':131 'also':299 'alter':875 'although':518 'appl':33 'approach':802 'arch':136 'arm':137 'arriv':665 'asphodel':192 'atour':160 'autumn':583 'ball':226 'bash':408 'basket':40 'bat':633 'beauti':35 'bed':197 'bee':244 'beech':17 'belt':812 'benefit':513 'berri':149 'besid':194 'bide':693 'bird':613 'blood':97,763 'bond':458 'boy':392 'brambl':146 'brick':277 'broader':555 'bud':700 'bushel':39 'bushel-basket':38 'busi':457 'call':515 'canal':191 'cannot':68