34	The Big Loser	10		\nThe guardian angel sits in the tree\r above the black lip of street\r the man walks down.\r He calls the man Cargo.\r The angel sees a pinewood box in place of the man,\r and the street he walks is a boat,\r the hull like a coal crater.\r Somewhere in the real world there is such a boat and box.\r The angels call these overlays dreams,\r and believe they crop up because angels\r can’t sleep but want to — \r space falls apart when you have unlimited time.\r  \r  • \r The cargo is rattling in the boat.\r Maybe it’s just the waves, maybe it’s rats.\r What’s the difference? Either way: it’s the box.\r The angel sends the man\r a happy vision from his past — the time\r he fed birthday cake\r to his goldfish\r after an unsuccessful party.\r The angel thinks he’s applying lemon oil\r to the creaky, wounded wood of the box.\r He knows it’s palliative, but it’s beautiful.\r  \r • \r The man reaches the end of the street. He’s a sick man\r and he starts to ponder death\r as he often does these days:\r All of death is right here\r — the gods, the dark, a moon.\r Where was I expecting death\r to take me if everywhere it is\r is on earth?\r At life’s close, you’re like the child whose parents\r step out for a drive — \r everyone else out on a trip,\r but the child remains in the familiar bed,\r feeling old lumps like new\r in the mattress — the lights off — \r not sleeping, for who can sleep\r with the promise of a world beyond the door?\r  \r • \r That night the child dreams\r he’s inside the box.\r It’s burning hot, the heat coming\r from bugs and worms\r raping and devouring one another.\r He starts the hard work\r of the imagination,\r learning to minister to the new dream.\r Perhaps all that’s needed is a little rain — \r for everyone to drink and have a bath.\r Outside: a car humming,\r somewhere, his mother’s singing.\n	'angel':6,27,64,75,118,142 'anoth':299 'apart':84 'appli':146 'bath':331 'beauti':165 'bed':247 'believ':70 'beyond':271 'big':2 'b