35	Dawn of Man	10		\nAfter the cocoon I was in a human body\r instead of a butterfly’s. All along my back\r there was great pain — I groped to my feet\r where I felt wings behind me, trying\r to tilt me back. They succeeded in doing so\r after a day of exertion. I called that time,\r overwhelmed with the ghosts of my wings, sleep.\r My thoughts remained those of a caterpillar — \r I took pleasure in climbing trees. I snuck food\r into all my pains. My mouth produced language\r which I attempted to spin over myself\r and rip through happier and healthier.\r I’d do this every few minutes. I’d think to myselfWhat made me such a failure?\r It’s all a little touchingly pathetic. To live like this,\r a grown creature telling ghost stories,\r staring at pictures, paralyzed for hours.\r And even over dinner or in bed — \r still hearing the stories, seeing the pictures — \r an undertow sucking me back into myself.\r I’m told to set myself goals. But my mind\r doesn’t work that way. I, instead, have wishes\r for myself. Wishes aren’t afraid\r to take on their own color and life — \r like a boy who takes a razor from a high cabinet\r puffs out his cheeks and strips them bloody.\n	'afraid':186 'along':19 'aren':184 'attempt':90 'back':21,41,159 'bed':147 'behind':35 'bloodi':213 'bodi':12 'boy':197 'butterfli':16 'cabinet':205 'call':53 'caterpillar':70 'cheek':209 'climb':75 'cocoon':6 'color':192 'creatur':131 'd':102,109 'dawn':1 'day':49 'dinner':144 'doesn':172 'even':142 'everi':105 'exert':51 'failur':117 'feet':30 'felt':33 'food':79 'ghost':59,133 'goal':168 'great':24 'grope':27 'grown':130 'happier':98 'healthier':100 'hear':149 'high':204 'hour':140 'human':11 'instead':13,178 'languag':87 'life':194 'like':127,195 'littl':122 'live':126 'm':163 'made':113 'man':3 'mind':171 'minut':107 'mouth':85 'myselfwhat':112 'overwhelm':56 'pain':25,83 'paralyz':138 'pathet':124 'pictur':137,154 'pleasur':73 'produc':86 'puff':206 'razor':201 'remain':66 'rip':96 'see':152 'se