36	The House that Jack Built	11		\nthe first trees were felled\r and sailed in, wrecked, then slept\r an age in the northern sun, blackening\r to iron                    were found by horsemen\r leading their horses and raised as\r cloud’s axles, rafters of night, a god’s gates\r      were passed through, seen\r from miles off, rolled the sun\r and moon along their lintels, rooted,\r put out leaves                     for a second time\r creaked, tasted the rain, held\r the wind to their hearts while\r the horsemen streamed like\r their horses’ manes\r into the dark, their fires\r black smudge in the subsoil, their bridles\r of gold underground\r      lived long, grew great\r                   were a second time\r felled, dressed                   were sharpened to stakes\r and raised as a fort\r by farmers who’d followed their ploughs\r to the treeline for fuel\r to bake the pots\r their ashes were buried in\r with a scattering of grain\r like stars                 each small clay\r heaven still hangs in the earth\r      were overgrown,\r steered clear of\r      called dragon’s ribs\r                    devil’s cot                 were nested among, rotted\r down beside\r      harbored foxglove, eggshell\r owl pellet, primrose, honeycomb\r      were glazed, split\r                   put out buds of malachite, blossoms\r of salt, grew again, put out\r small translucent fruits named\r by the women who prized them\r teardrops, ice apples, clarities\r       were offered bread,\r dolls of woven grass, plaits of hair, coins\r with the obverse ground smooth, beads\r of  turquoise\r     twisted, straightened, filled\r with rooks, held again\r the wind to their hearts, creaked, scraped\r off the sunlight’s scales with their leaves, were\r a grove, grew\r manes of lichen, were murmured\r under, gave counsel on still nights\r of open doorways the dead came through\r on horseback or shouldering flails or bearing chimes\r of ice apples                       gave shelter\r      