50	The Poem You’ve Been Waiting For	23		\nI saw then the white-eyed man\r leaning in to see if I was ready\r yet to go where he has been waiting\r to take me. I saw then the gnawing\r sounds my faith has been making\r and I saw too that the shape it sings\r in is the color of cast-iron mountains\r I drove so long to find I forgot I had\r been looking for them, for the you\r I once knew and the you that was born\r waiting for me to find you. I have been\r twisting and turning across these lifetimes\r where forgetting me is what you do\r so you don’t have to look at yourself. I saw\r that I would drown in a creek carved out\r of a field our incarnations forged the first path\r through to those mountains. I invited you to stroll\r with me there again for the first time, to pause\r and sprawl in the grass while I read to you\r the poem you hadn’t known you’d been waiting\r to hear. I read until you finally slept\r and all your jagged syntaxes softened into rest.\r You’re always driving so far from me towards\r the me I worry, without you, is eternity. I lay there,\r awake, keeping watch while you snored.\r I waited, as I always seem to, for you\r to wake up and come back to me.\n	'across':102 'alway':198,226 'awak':216 'back':236 'born':89 'carv':130 'cast':61 'cast-iron':60 'color':58 'come':235 'creek':129 'd':177 'drive':199 'drove':65 'drown':126 'etern':212 'eye':14 'faith':42 'far':201 'field':134 'final':186 'find':69,94 'first':139,156 'forg':137 'forget':106 'forgot':71 'gnaw':39 'go':26 'grass':164 'hadn':173 'hear':181 'incarn':136 'invit':146 'iron':62 'jag':191 'keep':217 'knew':83 'known':175 'lay':214 'lean':16 'lifetim':104 'long':67 'look':75,118 'make':45 'man':15 'mountain':63,144 'path':140 'paus':159 'poem':2,171 're':197 'read':167,183 'readi':23 'rest':195 'saw':9,36,48,122 'see':19 'seem':227 'shape':52 'sing':54 'slept':187 'snore':221 'soften':193 'sound':40 'sprawl':161 'stroll':149 'syntax':192 'take':33 'time':157 'toward':204 'turn':101 'tw