61	And Now She Has Disappeared in Water	34		\napril 1 \r found on our driveway\r   like a feather dropped     by a crow\r  \r \r   8 of spades,        a playing    card /\r  \r \r        we played Crazy Eights, slapping        cards or holding them        as if they were birds that might fly        out of our hands \r decades ago, in our childhood\r        like the translucent, whirling        image I imagine, prismatic and phosphorescent —         a murmuration of starlings swooping        and iridescent \r but it dissolved onto a gray wall, undecorated\r        / glimpses of us wearing our        velvet Sunday best dresses, yours        usually crimson, mine blue\r  \r \r        we never had nice shoes. \r Now you have returned to water\r  thanks to the Neptune Society spreading        your ashes over the Pacific\r  \r  \r  april 2\r  \r Ceylon tea — that amber cup\r             from Sri Lanka, popularly known here, before\r             Americans became tea drinkers, as\r                  Orange Pekoe;\r                         our mother hated\r                         so many things — \r                                               tea was\r                                    rattlesnake venom to\r                                                                      her\r             I embraced it  ///\r             What did you drink, Marilyn? I saw you only\r with a Coke or a glass of wine in your hand?\r Our mother whom you felt\r damaged you / your life       spirals, the twisting iridescent birds\r               fly at me now                       scintillating, spinning\r                                      I blink\r (Our mother drank many cups of coffee with cream a day.)\r Our sad mother\r                                    I blink\r                                    and tell it to go back to our childhood\r                                    of muddy little shoes from walking in\r                                    the spider-filled orange groves.\r There, the damaging must have Begun  / she\r                                    loving me so much\r                                                                       more\r                                                                       than you.\r I wish there had been more stories\r like the one about the origin of her disliking tea\r             at 17, she went to celebrate being made teacher\r             of the one-room school she had attended and\r             graduated from at her retiring teacher’s\r             home, she was served for the first time — tea, she\r             being from a German coffee-drinking family.\r             Our mother hated it but politely choked it down.\r             Would never again touch a drop of the\r             poisonous beverage.\r From that story, we learned that\r our mother ritualized hating something — expected us\r to admire her for it.\r                         I took\r                         that negative pattern\r                         and spun it until I could have cloth enough\r for an eloquent garment. Perhaps the lesson simply made you\r feel yourself            helpless         ragged                      torn\r I never\r saw you that way, Marilyn,\r though perhaps incomplete.\r I pour a cup of Assam. Take a sip,\r             let it wash through my mouth,\r                         down my age-damaged throat,\r think\r of you sitting\r with me in your Southern California \r backyard one May morning\r next to the camellia bush.\r I, as always with a cup of tea in my hand.\r You, smoking.\r I left all my family — you were part of it — \r left California and reinvented myself, even\r mythologized myself as a tan “California Girl.”\r You did not become an artist or a poet.\r I suppose that’s why you felt damaged.\r If only you knew how much imagination and sacrifice\r it took for me to get away.\r                         So many small things\r                                    can save us\r                                              from the damage\r you talked of. For me, drinking that\r first cup of Orange Pekoe\r and making tea\r my drink      risking rattlesnake poison\r with every steaming cup,\r a tiny emblem of a rebellion I still try to practice.\r You left us so quickly, Marilyn,\r and without any warning this January,\r your house full of cancelled aspirations — glass\r bowls, and cylinders, and huge globes\r filled with sea scallop shells\r             you combed the California seashores to \r                         find, collecting these empty shells, washed\r free of their biological life.                                 Out of the ocean:\r we two different daughters of a sailor.\r  \r april 3 \r The spinning                      the scissors               the measuring\r and thus our lives are given out\r from the heavens, with unfair allotments\r and varied, unaccountable fates,\r born when we are, and to whom\r you would have prevailed\r in an age where women had to spin,\r weave the material, cut it into britches and dresses,\r undergarments and sheets, sew\r and keep clean, warm, and comfortable a\r household full or a castle full / men\r children, hired hands, maidservants — you would have\r done it\r so well.\r But you would have died young in such a world — \r diabetes, asthma, chronic bronchial infections\r even in the 21st century where you lived to be\r 76       a world where all your skills were plied as\r             substitute\r for being an artist.\r                       When I asked you a year ago,\r not knowing that you would die this January,\r what you would most like to have, if\r money were not the object\r              — since clearly all your measuring, cutting, and sewing\r             had been for economical reasons,\r             not art — \r you thought for a bit, raising your chin.\r “A swimming pool in my backyard. One I could\r step into every morning, swim, float — maybe in the afternoon\r I’d go for a dip. Many evenings, I think,” she said\r to me.                     Longing for some ocean? \r In our portrait,\r if someone paints it, she will be \r sitting in a scallop shell,\r her many jars of seashells behind her head. I\r will be invisible, except for the spinning \r murmuration of birds that radiates\r             past me. \r They read at her funeral, a poem from her journal\r about lying on the beach,\r the sand embracing her.\r How much she loved it / felt safe,\r felt released. Oh, Marilyn, all\r those seashells emptied of their living\r fleshy occupants. (the ugly parts that die and rot) now\r glorious empty rooms\r             in which to live an imaginary life,\r                         to decorate,\r to create beauty, \r             spaces to live\r                         a different life.\r What is left but your desires, locked in glass, and\r an image of you walking\r your beloved beaches, hands \r full of seashells, your\r footprints measured, then quickly filled \r with the tidal flow.\r  \r april 4 \r my spinning, \r             a whirlpool of faceted moving lights\r                         Everything is Numbers!\r down into a vortical glare that replaces\r             my own mind’s desire \r                         Everything is Numbers! Everything is Numbers!\r floating down\r             like the crow’s\r                         onyx feather\r the 8\r             of spades\r                         random card\r appearing\r             last week\r                         over gravel\r 8 legs on a spider,\r             the arachnid so many people seem to\r             fear, yet I lose track of time, stare into the wall\r             or any space to replace real images with my imaginary\r             ones, some random spider, who spins my fate\r Crazy Eights, the child card game Marilyn and I played\r pieces of eight, the dollar of\r             pirate Spain — our childhood in Orange County\r 8, a vertical infinity sign\r             everything is numbers / your\r                         fire opal that Daddy brought\r to you from India, and our mother\r paid a jeweler to set it\r into a ring. You wore the ring\r more than sixty years. I suppose it was\r on your finger at death\r spinning,     spinning\r to scintillate and iridesce\r             We never had nice shoes.\r  \r april 5 \r Easter Sunday. You and I always dyed\r Easter eggs together, our mother busy at\r her forty-hour-a-week bookkeeper’s job. I \r was intrigued with the colors,\r but they never turned out so bright when\r coloring the eggs. You, the artist,\r were interested in the designs\r to transfer onto the eggs,\r cartoons, bunnies,\r chicks.\r We kept our eggs\r separated from each other,\r put them in separate bowls, neither\r caring for the other’s creation. Still we\r felt connected, even joyful, on those few holiday projects.\r Not enough to make us friends.\r My unwillingness to be like our classmates\r embarrassed you. You chose invisibility\r in school, rather than being known as “Diane’s\r Sister.” \r That unwillingness to be like others \r was what made me a poet. So many little things, but that early decision\r of yours, not to understand why I wanted to be weird,\r is what made you make so \r many other small choices, preventing you \r from becoming an artist. “Look away,” our mother said to us,\r when there were ugly things confronting us. \r I could not do that. You blame\r our mother, yet it was you who decided to look away,\r even though it meant not seeing the whole world,\r even if meant you didn’t become an artist.\r Poverty, of course, was the reason\r we never had nice shoes.\r  \r april 6 \r All numbers have\r disappeared\r                         instead\r             there are mushrooms\r             fungi that has always seemed\r             more artful than tasty\r             Sipping a cup of tea / soothes me\r             as the mushrooms in a veloute sauce\r             never could.\r             I feel stymied / a rider\r             with no horse. I want only to watch\r             the stories unfold / the secret stories about why\r             you chose to marry and have children / why\r             I did not / the stories\r                                     I try to banish\r             blot out, replace with the diamond\r             dog. A murmuration of iridescent starlings, \r             and the spider of eight, \r             twirling on its silk line, projecting infinity      art\r             is made when you subject yourself\r             to the unacceptable, then dredge\r             yourself out,\r                                     find a mineral replacement:\r             infinity\r             iridescer\r             irised feather\r             scintillater\r                         a crystalline body whirls\r             releasing me from\r             the history, the stories it’s\r             so hard to tell.\r Until recent years, my sister\r and I either ignored or disliked each other.\r We fought continuously as children.\r I have in my wrist a black bump that\r protrudes near a vein.\r                                     It’s the point of a pencil\r that broke off and penetrated my wrist as we struggled\r for the long yellow weapon.\r A pencil, the weapon of a writer. But there was \r no bleeding, no seeming-wound to be dressed. \r We never told\r our Mother, both too ashamed\r of our brutality. I’ve never asked a doctor\r about it, the pencil lead encapsulated\r in my wrist. Nor ever spoken\r of it to anyone.\r I always wonder that so much must remain a secret?\r Why\r             we never had nice shoes.\r  \r april 7 \r Young Marilyn, Old Marilyn.\r there are places on this planet where\r I find it hard to detect any beauty\r therefore, silence\r                         No nice shoes.\r  \r april 8 \r there is silence\r  \r april 9 \r Drinking\r a blend of traditional\r Darjeeling with a touch of Ceylon / this\r tea takes me back to a Viennese visit, drinking\r this very tea in the afternoon while my friend, Jonathan,\r ate their famous Sacher torte.\r The tea\r seemed particularly aromatic — \r             “lightly scented with oil of bergamot\r             and a hint of genuine Bourbon vanilla.”\r Wishing for the moment in the past to reappear. I didn’t know\r the tea from the Sacher Hotel\r was as famous as the cake\r                                 until I found in my Upton Tea catalogue\r                                 a listing for “Scented Darjeeling”\r                                 under the heading “Earl Grey Blends”\r This tea,\r any cup of tea!\r Hard to believe. no! Sad to\r think my Mother almost spat out her first taste\r of tea.\r What worldly thing must I touch to\r bring Marilyn back into my\r sedate life, my sister Marilyn who died in January? \r Her hand — I’d like to imagine timidly touching her\r       hand — Marilyn’s hand.\r             Her right hand on which she wore the fire opal ring.\r                         In that hand she’d be holding a cigarette.\r Smoke and fire makes me think of her — \r             not water, though it was that Pacific ocean \r                         filled with seashells\r                                     that she was in touch with. My old hands,\r not really like hers at all. She had big hands for shaping things,\r             while mine are small,      like birds.\n	'1':9 '17':262 '2':115 '21st':693 '3':594 '4':942 '5':1114 '6':1339 '7':1597 '76':700 '8':21,981,991,1055,1623 '9':1628 'admir':338 'afternoon':784,1655 'age':399,631 'age-damag':398 'ago':49,721 'allot':613 'almost':1742 'alway':423,1120,1351,1581 'amber':119 'american':128 'anyon':1579 'appear':986 'april':8,114,593,941,1113,1338,1596,1622,1627 'arachnid':997 'aromat':1669 'art':757,1354,1435 'artist':462,714,1157,1276,1326 'ash':110 'asham':1554 'ask':717,1561 'aspir':552 'assam':386 'asthma':686 'ate':1660 'attend':278 'away':489,1278,1308 'back':213,1644,1759 'backyard':412,771 'b