64	The Jews that We Are	35		\nI.   March 1979 and I am watching Nazis\r march through Chicago. The bold type\r of the Sun-Times describes a small band\r of hoodlums, undereducated boy scouts, the better\r to be ignored. My grandfather, back hunched\r over his Bible, agrees. Jews like myself\r should stay home, should lay down our stones\r and pray like the Jews that we are.\r  \r II.   Grandfather, you are easy to love\r with your long beard and the way you sway\r like a palm branch in the storm. It is easy\r to romanticize your spiritual search,\r worldly naiveté and wise rabbinical words.\r You belong in the books I read\r by Singer, Peretz, Sholom Aleichem.\r But their characters are ignorant\r of the chapters to come. You know\r where their prayers will lead.\r  \r III.   A circle. Six Nazis. Your wife in the middle.\r One soldier says all Jewesses are whores\r and the others agree. You say nothing.\r Years later you'll decide to speak:\r "Do we not serve Hitler's purpose, we\r who would sooner renounce our beliefs\r than assume our burdens?"\r  \r IV.   A generation after the Holocaust\r and I know no Hebrew. No Yiddish. No Torah.\r I fast only on the Day of Atonement\r and even then I've been known to cheat.\r A generation after the Holocaust\r and I apologize for my grandfather's\r bent back and wild gestures.\r I used to tremble to the rhythm\r of his prayers. I feared the mysterious\r words that kept us from the devil.\r Now, from my window I watch Nazis march.\r Their feet strike the pavement\r like the ticking of a clock. I am a Jew\r a generation after the Holocaust.\r Poorer, my grandfather says, without a past\r than he, who has no future.\r  \n	'1979':8 'agre':46,152 'aleichem':114 'apolog':220 'assum':178 'aton':203 'back':41,226 'band':28 'beard':76 'belief':176 'belong':104 'bent':225 'better':35 'bibl':45 'bold':18 'book':107 'boy':32 'branch':85 'burden':180 'chapter':122 'charact':117 'cheat':212 'chicago':16 'circl':134 'clock':269 'come':124 '