68	A Small Story	39		\nWhen Mrs. McCausland comes to mind\r she slips through a small gap in oblivion\r and walks down her front steps, in her hand\r a small red velvet pillow she tucks\r under the head of Old Jim Schreiber,\r who is lying dead-drunk against the curb\r of busy Market Street. Then she turns,\r labors up the steps and is gone . . .\r A small story. Or rather, the memory\r of a story I heard as a boy. The witnesses\r are not to be found, the steps lead nowhere,\r the pillow has collapsed into a thread of dust . . .\r Do the dead come back only to remind us\r they, too, were once among the living,\r and that the story we make of our lives\r is a mystery of luminous, but uncertain moments,\r a shuffle of images we carry toward sleep—\r Mrs. McCausland with her velvet pillow,\r Old Jim at peace—a story, like a small\r clearing in the woods at night, seen\r from the windows of a passing train.\n	'among':112 'back':103 'boy':78 'busi':51 'carri':137 'clear':155 'collaps':93 'come':7,102 'curb':49 'dead':45,101 'dead-drunk':44 'drunk':46 'dust':98 'found':85 'front':22 'gap':15 'gone':63 'hand':26 'head':36 'heard':75 'imag':135 'jim':39,147 'labor':57 'lead':88 'lie':43 'like':152 'live':114,123 'lumin':128 'make':120 'market':52 'mccausland':6,141 'memori':70 'mind':9 'moment':131 'mrs':5,140 'mysteri':126 'night':160 'nowher':89 'oblivion':17 'old':38,146 'pass':167 'peac':149 'pillow':31,91,145 'rather':68 'red':29 'remind':106 'schreiber':40 'seen':161 'shuffl':133 'sleep':139 'slip':11 'small':2,14,28,65,154 'step':23,60,87 'stori':3,66,73,118,151 'street':53 'thread':96 'toward':138 'train':168 'tuck':33 'turn':56 'uncertain':130 'us':107 'velvet':30,144 'walk':19 'window':164 'wit':80 'wood':158
