92	The Anti-Grief	59		\nDay after day of rain. A ticket straight to\r the mild-mannered hell of rethinking whatever,\r the drive to EconoFoods: not a lot of grief in that.\r You need staples — bread, rice, eggs.\r Here’s a list: almonds, yogurt, all the little\r anti-griefs add up.\r Did I tell you? my grandfather sings from the grave.\r They have my old Philco here.\r I know all about your world of godawful and too bad.\r I keep driving. In rain. Some luck required. Stop light.\r Flashy cars on both sides playing radios too loud.\r Ear damage! I used to shout out the window,\r my boy in the front seat trying hard to shrink, not to know\r who is that crazy at the wheel.\r Grandfather likes saying: what? Half-deaf even now.\r Half a lot of things, anytime. Half, what gives?\r giving way. If there is a we or a you or an I finally.\r He’d cup an ear if he had an ear.\r So it is, the first anti-grief, a feather he picked up.\r My childhood, walking with\r the oldest man I ever, 1874 his\r start date. Alarm and Should Have, two roads\r he would not cross, and Consequence\r a street over, he ignored completely. Always\r an eye out for the great\r small peculiar.\r A feather. Sometimes handed to me. Or he’d\r oil a clock with it right off the curb.\r Into a pocket.\n	'1874':192 'add':51 'alarm':196 'almond':43 'alway':214 'anti':3,49,176 'anti-grief':2,48,175 'anytim':142 'bad':79 'boy':109 'bread':36 'car':91 'childhood':184 'clock':234 'complet':213 'consequ':207 'crazi':124 'cross':205 'cup':162 'curb':240 'd':161,231 'damag':100 'date':195 'day':5,7 'deaf':134 'drive':23,82 'ear':99,164,169 'econofood':25 'egg':38 'even':135 'ever':191 'eye':216 'feather':179,224 'final':159 'first':174 'flashi':90 'front':112 'give':145,146 'godaw':76 'grandfath':58,128 'grave':62 'great':220 'grief':4,30,50,177 'half':133,137,143 'half-deaf':132 'hand':226 'hard':115 'hell':18 'ignor':212 'keep':81 'know':70,120 'light':89 'like':129 'list':42 'littl':47 'lot':28,139 'loud':98 'luck'