117	Life is a Carnival	71		\nDinner finished, wine in hand, in a vaguely competitive spirit\r of disclosure, we trail Google Earth's invisible pervert\r through the streets of our hometowns, but find them shabbier,\r      or grossly\r  \r contemporized, denuded of childhood's native flora,\r stuccoed or in some other way hostile\r to the historical reenactments we expect of our former\r  \r settings. What sadness in the disused curling rinks, their illegal\r basement bars imploding, in the seed of a Walmart\r sprouting in the demographic, in Street View's perpetual noon.\r      With pale\r  \r and bloated production values, hits of AM radio rise\r to the surface of a network of social relations long obsolete.\r      We sense\r a loss of rapport. But how sweet the persistence\r  \r of angle parking! Would we burn these places rather than see\r      them\r change, or just happily burn them, the sites of wreckage\r from which we staggered with our formative injuries into the rest\r  \r of our lives. They cannot be consigned to the fourfold,\r though the age we were belongs to someone else. Like our old\r house. Look what they've done to it. Who thought this would\r      be fun?\r  \r A concert, then, YouTube from those inconceivable days before\r YouTube, an era boarded over like a bankrupt country store,\r cans still on its shelves, so hastily did we leave it. How beautiful\r  \r they are in their poncey clothes, their youthful higher\r registers, fullscreen, two of them dead now. Is this eternity?\r Encore, applause, encore; it's almost like being there.\n	'age':166 'almost':246 'angl':122 'applaus':242 'bankrupt':206 'bar':70 'basement':69 'beauti':221 'belong':169 'bloat':91 'board':202 'burn':126,137 'can':209 'cannot':158 'carniv':4 'chang':133 'childhood':39 'cloth':227 'competit':13 'concert':191 'consign':160 'contempor':36 'countri':207 'curl':65 'day':197 'dead':236 'demograph':81 'denud':37 'dinner':5 'disclosur':16 'disus':64 'done':181 'earth':20 'els':17