131	Offerings	74		\nYears since I’d been back\r to the memorial; I’d forgotten\r  \r it was up on a rise above\r the killing ground. Two kids\r  \r appeared in the dust with things\r to sell—once coming from the far\r  \r end of the chain-link, two kinds\r of dream-catchers hanging\r  \r from his arm; and the girl, hunched\r on the broken steps under\r  \r the arch’s improbable cross, cradling\r a Tupperware bowl of beaded\r  \r star-necklaces in her lap. Her pink-\r and-silver t-shirt read PRINCESS.\r  \r I shut my car door, and a grouse\r startled off the fence, veered away\r  \r over bent switchgrass. The girl—\r Allie—said her little sisters made\r  \r the jewelry, in the gray house\r at the base of the hill; maybe\r  \r her price included the pictures I\r walked behind her to take: the marker\r  \r for 1890, then the more recent\r graves, in ground seared and\r  \r hardpanned by wind and snow and\r desolation; tied, bandana-pouches\r  \r of tobacco, and ribbons, like fists\r and fingers shifting and fluttering;\r  \r a few tough bright flowers left;\r gray-blue sky rolling above\r  \r to the edges of horizon all around,\r spitting, cooking up a storm.\r  \r I stood and turned back toward\r the arch again, where Allie and\r  \r her friend, if he was a friend, hadn’t\r spoken a word to one another.\r  \r For the first time in my life\r I wished I’d had some cigarettes—\r  \r to smoke with them, at least offer,\r something to do with strangers you\r  \r might sit a while beside till maybe\r one of you thought of something\r  \r to say. A little thunder crackled,\r and we said goodbye; I drove on\r  \r toward the shaft of rain above\r Manderson.  No reason to think I’d\r  \r be any memory to them; a dream-\r catcher sold, a brilliant blue\r  \r necklace. I passed a knocked-overvote Democrat sign, and two younger\r  \r kids working on a bike upside-down,\r and remembered the small bowls,\r  \r empty now, brought and offered\r at the graves surrounded for miles\r  \r by graves never found. Rain would\r fill them, lift the reservoirs, clear\r  \r the air. I thought of reaching over\r to pop the camera-back open; turned\r  \r from dirt onto narrow blacktop,\r the road out, that was steaming.\n	'1890':143 'air':353 'alli':110,209 'and-silv':83 'anoth':225 'appear':26 'arch':65,206 'arm':54 'around':193 'away':104 'back':7,203,364 'bandana':162 'bandana-pouch':161 'base':124 'bead':74 'behind':136 'bent':106 'besid':257 'bike':320 'blacktop':371 'blue':183,303 'bowl':72,328 'bright':178 'brilliant':302 'broken':61 'brought':331 'camera':363 'camera-back':362 'car':94 'catcher':50,299 'chain':43 'chain-link':42 'cigarett':239 'clear':351 'come':35 'cook':195 'crackl':271 'cradl':69 'cross':68 'd':5,12,236,291 'democrat':311 'desol':159 'dirt':368 'door':95 'dream':49,298 'dream-catch':48 'drove':277 'dust':29 'edg':189 'empti':329 'end':39 'far':38 'fenc':102 'fill':346 'finger':171 'first':228 'fist':169 'flower':179 'flutter':174 'forgotten':13 'found':343 'friend':212,217 'girl':57,109 'goodby':275 'grave':148,336,341 'gray':120,182 'gray-blu':181 'ground':23,150 'grous':98 'hadn':218 'hang':51 'hardpan':153 'hill':127 'horizon':191 'hous':121 'hunch':58 'improb':67 'includ':131 'jewelri':117 'kid':25,316 'kill':22 'kind':46 'knock':309 'knocked-overvot':308 'lap':80 'least':245 'left':180 'life':232 'lift':348 'like':168 'link':44 'littl':113,269 'made':115 'manderson':285 'marker':141 'mayb':128,259 'memori':10,294 'might':253 'mile':339 'narrow':370 'necklac':77,304 'never':342 'offer':1,246,333 'one':224,260 'onto':369 'open':365 'overvot':310 'pass':306 'pictur':133 'pink':82 'pop':360 'pouch':163 'price':130 'princess':90 'rain':283,344 'reach':357 'read':89 'reason':287 'recent':147 'rememb':325 'reservoir':350 'ribbon':167 'rise':19 'road':373 'roll':185 'said':111,274 'say':267 'sear':151 'sell':33 'shaft':281 'shift':172 'shirt':88 'shut':92 'sign':312 'silver':85 'sinc':3 'sister':114 'sit':254 'sky':184 'small':327 's