145	Warhol/Mao, '72	31		\nWhen I saw his face on a wall\r at a party in a parlor looking out at the Hudson,\r  \r at a fundraiser for the winter soldiers\r over blocks of cheese and baguettes,\r  \r I had just come from some grainy footage\r of Dien Bien Phu in a hot black room,\r  \r where the scratched print showed the hills undulating,\r bodies and parachutes disappearing in jungle grass.\r  \r Between decadence and the alien\r Mao was propped in yellow and rouge\r  \r with lipstick and eye shadow,\r a real queen—part décor, part radical something\r  \r the American lexicon hadn’t filled in yet.\r  \r From the aerial cameras\r Haiphong Harbor was liquid light.\r  \r In liquid light, I saw my draft card float like a\r giant litho over the highway at 79th\r  \r the letters popped—selective service system—\r and morphed into gray rain—\r  \r anyone could have done it—\r singed, blurred, laminated—\r  \r and the bartender poured me\r another unidentified drink.\r  \r In the scratched cellulose nitrite, parachutes\r kept drifting down on the hedges of the Laotian border.\r  \r On the wall Mao was the punctum\r in rouge and yellow and smear.\r  \r Didn’t every myth signify confusion?\r Confucius, Charlie Chan, Chiang Kai-shek?\r  \r (An American vision of a place.)\r  \r The guy behind me in class asked,\r “Where is this place?”\r  \r Hanoi was glittering flecks on the nightly news,\r and the teacher answered,\r  \r “Every snake of land is someone’s history.”\r  \r We didn’t know what we didn’t know about\r the backyard furnaces, the tens of millions.\r  \r Even if Mao swallowed Darwin and Adam Smith\r swimming the Yangtze—here on the Upper West\r  \r in late spring, he was wallpaper,\r the most recognizable face in the world.\r  \r There seemed no point in breaking through the mask—\r I was glued to the colors for a while,\r  \r until the next war let us out of Asia\r until the sun went down on the wall.\n	'72':2 '79th':126 'adam':256 'aerial':102 'alien':71 'american