156	Zoloft	78		\nTwo weeks into the bottle of pills, I'd remember\r exiting the one-hour lens grinder at Copley Square—\r the same store that years later would be blown\r back and blood-spattered by a backpack\r bomb at the marathon. But this was back when\r terror happened elsewhere. I walked out\r wearing the standard Boston graduate student\r wire-rims, my first-ever glasses, and saw little people\r in office tower windows working late under fluorescent\r lights. File cabinets with drawer seams blossomed\r wire bins, and little hands answered little black\r telephones, rested receivers on bloused shoulders—\r real as the tiny flushing toilets, the paneled wainscotting\r and armed candelabras I gasped at as a child in \r the miniature room at the Art Institute in Chicago.\r It was October and I could see the edges\r of everything—where the branches had been a blur\r of fire, now there were scalloped oak leaves, leathery\r maple five-points plain as on the Canadian flag.\r When the wind lifted the leaves the trees went pale,\r then dark again, in waves. Exhaling manholes,\r convenience store tiled with boxed cigarettes\r and gum, the BPL's forbidding fixtures lit\r to their razor tips and Trinity's windows holding\r individual panes of glass between bent metal like\r hosts in a monstrance. It was wonderful. It made me\r horribly sad.\r                                                       It was the same	'answer':92 'arm':111 'art':125 'back':31,46 'backpack':38 'bent':211 'bin':88 'black':94 'blood':34 'blood-spatt':33 'blossom':86 'blous':99 'blown':30 'blur':146 'bomb':39 'boston':57 'bottl':6 'box':187 'bpl':192 'branch':142 'cabinet':82 'canadian':164 'candelabra':112 'chicago':128 'child':118 'cigarett':188 'conveni':183 'copley':20 'could':134 'd':10 'dark':177 'drawer':84 'edg':137 'elsewher':50 'ever':66 'everyth':139 'exhal':181 'exit':12 'file':81 'fire':148 'first':65 'first-ev':64 'five':158 'five-point':157 'fixtur':195 'flag':165 'fluoresc':79 'flush