162	My Nodebook for December	80		\n                  1\r  \r Closing the door is supposed to open some\r inward source—as with, for example, the prayer-\r closet: the text says go in and “shut thy door.”\r It's a stroke of luck when traditional\r wisdom so matches the turning of the season.\r  \r  \r                   2\r  \r I've ofen thought of writing a poem of grotesque\r length (an epic, yes) and setting the entire argument\r the instant after Gautama's enlightenment, while\r it seemed to him he would pass directly\r into Nirvana, while the powers of good trembled\r thinking man was lost. It was only an\r instant, because of course the Buddha\r reconsidered.\r  \r  \r                   3\r  \r Bulls for the bull-fight must (this is\r absolutely essential) be\r innocent. The very brightest are certainly,\r by human standards, stupid, but\r after a few fights the\r dullest among them would learn not to\r charge an empty cape but turn and\r massacre the fancy-pants who dances there\r for a bloody crowd. But, as Hemingway\r noted, the bull never survives. I can't, myself, get\r excited about “life and death, i.e., violent\r death,” and have never been able to\r work up much sympathy for\r the brute who runs with his\r head down or for the show-off, who\r has it coming. I'll probably never\r develop a taste for battle or\r get seven novels written or kill myself.\r  \r  \r                   4\r  \r History is hard for me. I’ve no\r sense for it.\r  \r  \r                   5\r  \r The world—and if ever there was a self-evident\r proposition, here it is—the worldis a big fish. I've caught it in\r my net. And now, long into the winter\r nights, wearily, I study my net.\r The fish stinks.\r  \r  \r                   6\r  \r A friend talks passionately in favor of\r silence. I listen to him. He says, “Silence\r dissolves the categories” and “Silence renews\r the potential of consciousness.” And it strikes me\r that I should say something.\r But I've never been able to argue. And whenever there’s\r been a choice between speaking and keeping still,\r I’ve kept my mouth shut. Well,\r usually. And only after\r a certain amount of prodding I’ve\r produced the necessary conventional sounds,\r feeling the thread of words I spew\r inordinately fragile, certainly nothing\r to depend on. Whereas the craw of\r silence is vast and, anyway,\r already has us—it’s the scorching sunlight\r of a Nilescape or the wind across the Great\r Plains, burying us. Friend, waist deep in dust or\r sand, maybe we’d contrive a gesture.\r  \r  \r                   7\r  \r I passed the peak of my\r energy at the age of—it's\r hard to believe—\r twelve. Since then,\r little by little, I've collected\r the furniture of my house.\r I teach meanwhile, and I\r study, but no one knows\r my specialty.\r  \r  \r                   8 XMAS [after Pessoa]\r  \r A God is born. Some other Gods die. Truth\r has neither come nor gone, only the Error has changed.\r We have now another Eternity,\r and the world is no better off than it was.\r Blind Knowing plows a sterile plain\r Lunatic Faith lives a dream of worship.\r A new God is nothing but a word.\r Seek not. Nor believe. All is occult.\r  \r  \r                   9\r  \r Time is molecular—so much for\r Zeno—and each moment brings everything\r out of nothing. In the beginning (each\r beginning) the universe is only a\r point—no dimension—and then\r it’s a world, for a moment, and\r each moment is apocalypse. Continuous creation it used to be called, and now\r we say expanding universe because (I\r forgot to say) each moment is more. Whatever else it may\r be, it's always more. No wonder the poet cries\r “Oh,Oh,”\r or, on a higher level, lyrical verses. But don’t\r worry. I’m not violent. We all\r live in a residue of\r bright pulsations, a gob\r of time, an after-image.\r  \r  \r                   10\r  \r How naive can you get?—I\r was wondering, when the Great\r Year comes around to this point again\r and the next me sits signing his\r poems Keith Waldrop, will he\r remember back across the void\r of Decembers to where I drift into these\r speculations? And a moment’s\r thought answers my stupid question: I\r remember nothing.\r  \r  \r                   11\r  \r When I think of the books you could\r fill with what I don’t know, oof. The pressing need’s\r for a phenomenology of ignorance. Everything has\r horizons, and they’re not just\r out of sight, they loom. Yes, and they beckon.\r An open door is plain and simple, like a\r wall. A closed door is an invitation. But if\r the knob is turning . . . ?\r Well, I’m closing in, or opening up. I’ve been so\r bloody finicky the mysteries catch me sometimes\r with my lids down. But I’m preparing. I need\r many voices for my revenge.\n	'1':5 '10':639 '11':696 '2':48 '3':106 '4':228 '5':240 '6':283 '7':417 '8':460 '9':526 'abl':186,323 'absolut':116 'across':398,672 'after-imag':636 'age':427 'alreadi':384 'alway':598 'among':136 'amount':351 'anoth':486 'answer':689 'anyway':383 'apocalyps':568 'argu':325 'argument':67 'around':653 'back':671 'battl':219 'beckon':738 'begin':544,546 'believ':433,522 'better':493 'big':259 'blind':498 'bloodi':159,773 'book':702 'born':467 'bright':629 'brightest':122 'bring':537 'brute':194 'buddha':104 'bull':107,111,166 'bull-fight':110 'buri':402 'call':575 'cape':145 'catch':777 'categori':301 'caught':263 'certain':124,350,370 'chang':482 'charg':142 'choic':332 'close':6,750,764 'closet':22 'collect':442 'come':210,475,652 'conscious':308 'continu':569 'contriv':414 'convent':359 'could':704 'cours':102 'craw':377 'creation':570 'cri':604 'crowd':160 'd':413 'danc':155 'death':178,181 'decemb':4,676 'deep':406 'depend':373 'develop':215 'die':471 'dimens':554 'direct':82 'dissolv':299 'door':8,31,741,751 'dream':508 'drift':680 'dullest':135 'dust':408 'els':592 'empti':144 'energi':424 'enlighten':73 'entir':66 'epic':61 'error':480 'essenti':117 'etern':487 'ever':245 'everyth':538,722 'evid':251 '