164	Six Further Studies	80		\nI\r  \r In heaven there is no more sea, and houses no longer need a widow’s\r walk. And no more widows, there being neither marriage nor giving\r in marriage. How the air hangs lower and lower on this—I hope\r —hottest day of summer. A faintly rotten scent the ground gives off\r brings to mind lilacs that have budded and blossomed. There are no\r more blossoms, perfume and purple gone for a year, as if forever. In\r heaven there are no tears, salt water wiped away entirely. One moment\r I breathe contentment. And then unreasoning sorrow pulses through\r me, an imperfect tension, as if unending. I have time on my hands. In\r heaven there is no more dusk, dark, dawn, meridian. And what I know\r now and for certain: neither the day nor the hour.\r  \r  \r II\r  \r It seems clear enough that there is in the brain a particular pain-center,\r where sensations of every variety check in, to emerge as anguish and\r hurt. Thus there is not, as we might suppose, a multiplicity of pains,\r like an arsenal deployed against us, but one pain which puts on, as in a\r ritual theater, different masks.\r          It need not, even, be a great number of masks, some few faces\r peopling an endless repertory. From one fairy tale to another, is not\r the witch the same witch, whether poisoning an apple or fattening the\r children?\r  \r  \r III\r  \r The doctrine changes, blows here and there, hot, cold. One more\r notion sweeps across the state in gusts, fiercely at first, settling then\r into a mild rotation. It puts things in motion. It dies down, while\r pressure somewhere else is building.\r          Called to, across a chasm of thin air, I shape the air to answer. My\r moments force themselves apart.\r          Breathe out. Breathe in. But as long as you are alive, there is a dead\r space in your lungs, never emptied, never needing to be filled. The spirit\r there, stale and sustaining, holds open every possibility, urging none. Ghost\r money: money to burn.\r  \r  \r IV\r  \r On the earliest known sundial, the finger of shadow moves through\r symbols of the cosmos, but there are no lines drawn to mark off the hours.\r It does not, in the modern sense, “keep” time, but celebrates its flight, its\r recurrence, its brightness.\r  \r  \r V\r  \r Hermaphrodite, sleeping. Predominance, in the visible, of the right hand\r —but the eyes now closed. What could there be to dream about, for one\r already complete? A perfect asymmetrical stability. No need to see or even\r to look.\r          To know, without having to ask. From any point on the periphery,\r advancing always towards the body. Both sexes. And both asleep.\r  \r  \r VI\r  \r A scream from outside broke our argument and I ran to the door, rushed\r out onto the sidewalk almost, I thought, before the scream had ended. The\r night sky, above the street lamp, had a sheen of some dark metal.\r          Sirens—which seemed this evening more frequent than usual, and\r more strident—state the theme, you have said, of our instant: the howl\r of a machine hurrying to disaster. And all day, in the violence of delivery,\r ordinary trucks rattle our sashes.\r          The street lay empty, mercury lit, silence giving us no indication of\r which way to turn.\r  \n	'across':251,281 'advanc':436 'air':35,286,290 'aliv':308 'almost':465 'alreadi':410 'alway':437 'anguish':165 'anoth':221 'answer':292 'apart':297 'appl':232 'argument':453 'arsenal':182 'ask':429 'asleep':445 'asymmetr':414 'away':89 'blossom':64,69 'blow':241 'bodi':440 'brain':149 'breath':94,298,300 'bright':384 'bring':56 'broke':451 'bud':62 'build':278 'burn':340 'call':279 'celebr':378 'center':154 'certain':132 'chang':240 'chasm':283 'check':160 'children':236 'clear':142 'close':400 'cold':246 'complet':411 'content':95 'cosmos':356 'could':402 'dark':122,485 'dawn':123 'day':45,135,518 'dead':312 'deliveri':523 'deploy':183 'die':271 'differ':197 'disast':515 'doctrin':239 'door':459 'drawn':362 'dream