215	The Work	104		\n1. Today\rToday, this moment, speechlessly in pain,\rHe fights the terror of being poured out,\rThe fall into darkness unquenchably long\rSo that even as he hurtles he keeps holding\rBack like a dam the flood overtops—but nothing now\rCan stop that surge, already he swirls\rTo the source of Voices, the many throats inside the one\rThroat, each swallowing the unstoppable flood ...\rAnd as if that, all along, were what he'd wanted,\rHe hears the Voices begin to die down\rThe way a marsh in spring pulsing and shrilling\rSunup to sundown falls gradually still\r—Unappeasable, the silence that will follow\rWhen his every last drop has been poured out.\r          2. Countdown\rIn your hospital bed, the plastic mask across\rYour face siphoning air into your lungs,\rYou lie helpless as an astronaut\rBlasting into space: Eyes oblivious\rTo ours, your body's fevered presence\rShimmers like the phantom heat that will trail\rUp the pipe of the crematory oven:\rHow distant we will seem after\rSuch intensity ... We drift in your stare\rLike the dust stirred by the cow your parents\rGave you as a boy to teach responsibility.\rAlready you are space immeasurable\rBy your slide rule, your graphs that plotted\rPayload, liftoff, escape velocity.\r          3. Prayer\rIn the house of the dead I pace the halls:\rThe walls, collapsing, stretch away in desert\rOr flatten into horizonless ocean.\rI step outside, the door clicking shut\rComforting in its finality ...\rNow I see the house as if I looked down\rFrom far off mountains, and saw you crouching in\rThe sun-scoured yard, eyes keenly focused,\rPupils narrowing to a cat's green slits:\rI can't look you in the face, you see only\rThe openness of sky rising above mountains.\r(Only after the world had emptied\rYou and filled you with its openness\rWill I feel the love I pray to feel?)\r          4. The God\ra dream A warming pulsing flood like blood surging through\rVeins, and now the god stirs in my hands\rDull as stone in this gravity-less Nowhere.\rSensation shivering through me, deliberate and sure,\rI cradle you, I sponge you clean\rAs if you were my son, the emptiness you\rDrink like heavy black milk erasing\rYour wrinkles and gouged lines of pain.\rThe god bends me to the work, my fingers driven\rBy the god, blinded by the god's\rNeutrality, until I pull apart the threads\rIn this place the god commands:\rFace wholly unwoven, without heart, mind, you\rare nothing in my hands but my hands moving.\r          5. His Stare\rAbsently there in a moment of pure being\rHe sits in his chair, eyes locked, staring:\rThe air's transparence gains solidity\rFrom his looking; while his emaciated features,\rThe way his flesh sags from sharpening cheekbones,\rMake the summer air weigh like marble on the harsh green\rOf the trees he is too weak to prune.\rAnd yet the contemplative distance he is sealed in\rProjects with ferocious purpose the will of his body\rTo withdraw into this eerily removed contemplation\rLike one who has heard a tuning fork ringing\rAnd enters and becomes each spectral vibration;\rSo utterly absorbed that love is a distraction; even\rThe world, its barest colors, bleeding away before that stare.\r          6. The Current\rThe numbing current of the Demorol\rSweeps him out to sea where the secret night\rHe lives in slowly begins to darken,\rHis daytime routine of watching his blood cycle\rThrough the tubes of a machine shadowed by blackness\rBlinding as an underwater cave. Already\rHe filters the dark water through gills aligned\rTo strain that element he more and more resembles:\rLike walls of water held in miraculous\rSuspension, the moment of his death looms impartially\rAbove him, my hands holding his tightening\rIts grip even as his hand loosens ...\rAs if my hand could lead him past that undulating\rWeight towering above us out of sight.\r          7. The Rehearsal\rI lead you back, your Orpheus, until you\rStand inhaling, on the topmost stair,\rThe rank rich air of breathing flesh—\rBut like fumes rising from earth's molten core\rThe voices of the dead reach out to you,\rYour whispering parents, dead for forty years,\rEntreating me to turn—and so I\rTurn, as must you: Your footsteps die,\rYou dwindle, blur into unfillable\rSpace echoing like the dark of a cathedral ...\rBut there is no dark, no stair, no Orpheus\r—Only this voice rehearsing breath\rBy breath in words you'll never read these\rLines stolen from your death.\n	'1':3 '2':117 '3':214 '4':324 '5':438 '6':558 '7':669 'absent':441 'absorb':541 'across':126 'air':130,458,481,689 'align':613 'along':73 'alreadi':48,197,605 'apart':413 'astronaut':139 'away':230,554 'back':34,675 'barest':551 'becom':535 'bed':122 'begin':83,580 'bend':393 'black':381,599 'blast':140 'bleed':553 'blind':404,600 'blood':334,589 'blur':734 'bodi':148,515 'boy':193 'breath':691,758,760 'cat':280 'cathedr':744 'cave':604 'chair':453 'cheekbon':477 'clean':368 'click':243 'collaps':228 'color':552 'comfort':245 'command':421 'contempl':501,522 'core':701 'could':656 'countdown':118 'cow':186 'cradl':363 'crematori':165 'crouch':266 'current':560,563 'cycl':590 'd':77 'dam':37 'dark':22,609,741,749 'darken':582 'daytim':584 'dead':221,706,714 'death':635,772 'deliber':359 'demorol':566 'desert':232 'die':85,731 'distanc':502 'distant':168 'distract':546 'door':242 'dream':328 'drift':176 'drink':378 'driven':400 'drop':112 'dull':346 'dust':182 'dwindl':733 'earth':698 'echo':738 'eerili':520 'element':617 'emaci':468 'empti':307,376 'enter':533 'entreat':718 'eras':383 'escap':212 'even':27,547,647 'everi':110 'eye':143,273,454 'face':128,291,422 'fall':20,99 'far':260 'featur':469 'feel':317,323 'feroci':509 'fever':150 'fight':12 'fill':310 'filter':607 'final':248 'finger':399 'flatten':234 'flesh':473,692 'flood':39,67,332 'focus':275 'follow':107 'footstep':730 'fork':530 'forti':716 'fume':695 'gain':461 'gave':189 'gill':612 'god':326,341,392,403,407,420 'goug':387 'gradual':100 'gra