218	The Meadow	104		\nAcross the road from where we nap\runder a dead elm dazzles the meadow\rwhere the partisans strung the traitors up,\rthe meadow which their dangling shadows stain.\rBelly up in vines a blasted tank\rrusts flake by flake to lichened scrap iron\rwhile horseflies harangue\rthe rippling green, July\ra limbo of quavering yellow...\rWe wake to cattle lowing at dawn,\rgrass overgrowing summer—so like us\rin love each hour with the noonday sun\rthat neither toils nor spins, its brightness\rhovering, blinding us...\rWhat would the dead say if they could see us,\rlounging, talking, peering through brambles\rat cemetery photographs sunk beneath\rthe undertow of milkweed shadows,\rdeath dates smoothing back into the stone?\rI think of Goya’s demon, old man flesh\rhanging from his bones, long teeth bared in\ran ass’s grin as he scrawls on a schoolboy’s\rslate, What more can be done? Nothing... while behind him a noose etched clean as\rthe moon rises through the inkblot\rspiraling back into the hanged man’s mouth\ras if blackness poured from his throat:\r“When will you tire of us bogeymen,\rcaricatures of your father’s war,\rour crimes half-forgotten, unforgiven?\rAll future blotted out when they hauled us\rfrom our beds, our minds went dead\rto everything but fear: Nightshirts\rsoaked in snowlight’s pall, we hunched in mud, each step\rloud, too loud beside the farmhouse wall,\rthe seconds teetering till we drop...\rWhat our betrayals were we know\rwith a knowledge intimate beyond revenge,\rhistory the needle’s eye you can’t squeeze through.\rThe partisans cut us down, heaped us\rin a mass grave our relatives dug up: Yes,\rthere were tears—even for us...\rNow, like aliens from space on your TV shows,\rwe ravel into mist, surrounding\ryou the moment your eyes close...\rOur pupils search out yours from behind\rthe mirror with your father’s stares,\rfathers and sons melding in one mind—\rbut who are you to call us traitors, an outsider\rjudging through the smoke-haze of home:\rEach blow exact, our own neighbors\rbeat us till the blood ran, beat us black\rand blue...Even now, would they dare take us back,\rolder, wiser, necks broken by the yoke?\rMoving in time as to a dance we buzz\rand swarm across the meadow, dissolving\rand glinting like fireflies in the hedge,\rblown like milkweed in the moon’s wall eye.\rBut under your lids, you see us locked in cold,\rshattered wheatstraw flecked in ice:\rChill as the night air on your sunburned neck\rour eyes like X rays pierce the frost,\rstalking every step the living take.”\n	'across':3,394 'air':433 'alien':294 'ass':139 'back':117,171,375 'bare':136 'beat':357,363 'bed':214 'behind':157,318 'belli':31 'beneath':108 'besid':238 'betray':250 'beyond':258 'black':180,365 'blast':36 'blind':87 'blood':361 'blot':206 'blow':352 'blown':405 'blue':367 'bogeymen':191 'bone':133 'brambl':103 'bright':85 'broken':379 'buzz':391 'call':338 'caricatur':192 'cattl':61 'cemeteri':105 'chill':429 'clean':162 'close':311 'cold':423 'could':96 'crime':199 'cut':272 'danc':389 'dangl':28 'dare':372 'date':115 'dawn':64 'dazzl':14 'dead':12,92,218 'death':114 'demon':126 'dissolv':397 'done':154 'drop':247 'dug':283 'elm':13 'etch':161 'even':289,368 'everi':447 'everyth':220 'exact':353 'eye':264,310,413,439 'farmhous':240 'father':195,323,326 'fear':222 'firefli':401 'flake':39,41 'fleck':426 'flesh':129 'forgotten':202 'frost':445 'futur':205 'glint':399 'goya':124 'grass':65 'grave':280 'green':51 'grin':141 'half':201 'half-forgotten':200 'hang':130,174 'harangu':48 'haul':210 'haze':348 'heap':275 'hedg':404 'histori':260 'home':350 'horsefli':47 'hour':74 'hover':86 'hunch':230 'ice':428 'inkblot':169 'intim':257 'iron':45 'judg':343 'juli':52 'know':253 'knowledg':256 'lichen':43 'lid':417 'like':69,293,400,406,440 'limbo':54 'live':450 'lock':421 'long':134 'loud':235,237 'loung':99 'love':72 'low':62 'man':128,175 'mass':279 'meadow':2,16,25,396 'meld':329 'milkwe':112,407 'mind':216,