223	To Kill a Deer	106		\nInto the changes of autumn brush the doe walked, and the hide, head, and ears were the tinsel browns. They made her. I could not see her. She reappeared, stuffed with apples, and I shot her. Into the pines she ran, and I ran after. I might have lost her, seeing no sign of blood or scuffle, but felt myself part of the woods, a woman with a doe’s ears, and heard her dying, counted her last breaths like a song of dying, and found her dying. I shot her again because her lungs rattled like castanets, then poked her with the gun barrel because her eyes were dusty and unreal. I opened her belly and pushed the insides like rotted fruit into a rabbit hole, skinned her, broke her leg joints under my knee, took the meat, smelled the half-digested smell that was herself. Ah, I closed her eyes. I left her refolded in some briars with the last sun on her head like a benediction, head tilted on its axis of neck and barren bone; head bent wordless over a death, though I heard the night wind blowing through her fur, heard riot in the emptied head.\n	'ah':153 'appl':36 'autumn':9 'axi':179 'barrel':109 'barren':183 'belli':120 'benedict':174 'bent':186 'blood':59 'blow':197 'bone':184 'breath':83 'briar':164 'broke':134 'brown':23 'brush':10 'castanet':102 'chang':7 'close':155 'could':28 'count':80 'death':190 'deer':4 'die':79,88,92 'digest':148 'doe':12,73 'dusti':114 'ear':19,75 'empti':205 'eye':112,157 'felt':63 'found':90 'fruit':127 'fur':200 'gun':108 'half':147 'half-digest':146 'head':17,171,175,185,206 'heard':77,193,201 'hide':16 'hole':131 'insid':124 'joint':137 'kill':2 'knee':140 'last':82,167 'left':159 'leg':136 'like':84,101,125,172 'lost':53 'lung':99 'made':25 'meat':143 'might':51 'neck':181 'night':195 'open':118 'part':65 'pine':43 'poke':104 'push':122 'rabbit':130 'ran':45,48 'rattl':100 'reappear':33 'refold':161 'riot':202 'rot':126 'scuffl':61 'see':30,55 'shot':39,94 'sign':57 'skin':132 'smell':144,149 'song':86 'stuf':34 'sun