264	Yom Kippur, Taos, New Mexico	122		\nI’ve expanded like the swollen door in summer\r             to fit my own dimension. Your loneliness\r is a letter I read and put away, a daily reminder\r             in the cry of the magpie that I am\r still capable of inflicting pain\r             at this distance.\r Like a painting, our talk is dense with description,\r             half-truths, landscapes, phrases layered\r with a patina over time. When she came into my life\r             I didn’t hesitate.\r Or is that only how it seems now, looking back?\r             Or is that only how you accuse me, looking back?\r Long ago, this desert was an inland sea. In the mountains\r             you can still find shells.\r It’s these strange divagations I’ve come to love: midday sun\r             on pink escarpments; dusk on gray sandstone;\r toe-and-finger holes along the three hundred and fifty-seven foot\r             climb to Acoma Pueblo, where the spirit\r of the dead hovers about its earthly home\r             four days, before the prayer sticks drive it away.\r Today all good Jews collect their crimes like old clothes\r             to be washed and given to the poor.\r I remember how my father held his father around the shoulders\r             as they walked to the old synagogue in Philadelphia.\r "We're almost there, Pop," he said. "A few more blocks."\r             I want to tell you that we, too, are almost there,\r for someone has mapped this autumn field with meaning, and any day\r             October brooding in me, will open to reveal\r our names—inscribed or absent — \r             among the dry thistles and spent weeds.\n	'absent':257 'accus':96 'acoma':151 'ago':101 'almost':213,231 'along':140 'among':258 'around':199 'autumn':238 'away':29,172 'back':89,99 'block':221 'brood':246 'came':72 'capabl':43 'climb':149 'cloth':182 'collect':177 'come':123 'cri':35 'crime':179 'daili':31 'day':165,244 'dead':158 'dens':56 'descript':58 'desert':103 'didn':77 'dime