328	Antiphons of the Known World	159		\nAthena, coming onto me (verbatim transcription):Every step you take will be the right one.\r Women encouraged me like that:Avoiding void, no one goes nameless in this world.\r Power? I was the son of a king:Hacking the armor from the limbs of the dying.\r In the path of the blade of the plough I met God my foe:Oh blight his voyage with trial and calamity.\r All he needed was a taste of his own medicine:The water was white with the blades of our oars.\r Long-limbed Circe, the troubled, could only bring trouble:Sure enough that month became a year.\r Then Demodocus struck his lyre, and sang for me:In that soft song I led one hundred lives.\r I was young, singing such distance, when I set out:The meters were my cloak, my map, my axe.\r Declensions of the beasts defined my travels:I made the lions purr; the lions licked my hands.\r When gulls cry over rough water, home is close:I remembered Charybdis the Swallower, in her magnificence.\r Horizon-soaked, I sat and sobbed. Sunset. Shoulders shaking.This was the liver’s dying, the world’s waking.\n	'antiphon':1 'armor':45 'athena':6 'avoid':26 'axe':147 'beast':151 'becam':108 'blade':57,90 'blight':67 'bring':102 'calam':73 'charybdi':176 'circ':97 'cloak':143 'close':173 'come':7 'could':100 'cri':167 'declens':148 'defin':152 'demodocus':112 'die':51,196 'distanc':134 'encourag':22 'enough':105 'everi':12 'foe':65 'god':63 'goe':30 'gull':166 'hack':43 'hand':164 'home':171 'horizon':183 'horizon-soak':182 'hundr':127 'king':42 'known':4 'led':125 'lick':162 'like':24 'limb':48,96 'lion':158,161 'live':128 'liver':194 'long':95 'long-limb':94 'lyre':115 'made':156 'magnific':181 'map':145 'medicin':83 'met':62 'meter':140 'month':107 'nameless':31 'need':76 'oar':93 'oh':66 'one':20,29,126 'onto':8 'path':54 'plough':60 'power':35 'purr':159 'rememb':175 'right':19 'rough':169 'sang':117 'sat':186 'set':137 'shaking.this':191 'shoulder':190 'sing':132 'soak':184 'sob':188 'soft':1