346	Idea 14: If he from heaven that filched that living fire	168		\nIf he from heaven that filched that living fire Condemned by Jove to endless torment be, I greatly marvel how you still go free, That far beyond Prometheus did aspire. The fire he stole, although of heavenly kind, Which from above he craftily did take, Of liveless clods, us living men to make, He did bestow in temper of the mind. But you broke into heaven’s immortal store, Where virtue, honor, wit, and beauty lay; Which taking thence you have escaped away, Yet stand as free as ere you did before;    Yet old Prometheus punished for his rape.    Thus poor thieves suffer when the greater ‘scape.\n	'14':2 'although':46 'aspir':41 'away':94 'beauti':86 'bestow':67 'beyond':38 'broke':75 'clod':59 'condemn':21 'craftili':54 'endless':25 'ere':100 'escap':93 'far':37 'filch':8,17 'fire':11,20,43 'free':35,98 'go':34 'great':29 'greater':117 'heaven':6,15,48,77 'honor':83 'idea':1 'immort':79 'jove':23 'kind':49 'lay':87 'live':10,19,61 'liveless':58 'make':64 'marvel':30 'men':62 'mind':72 'old':105 'poor':112 'prometheus':39,106 'punish':107 'rape':110 'scape':118 'stand':96 'still':33 'stole':45 'store':80 'suffer':114 'take':56,89 'temper':69 'thenc':90 'thiev':113 'thus':111 'torment':26 'us':60 'virtu':82 'wit':84 'yet':95,104
347	Sonnet 1: From fairest creatures we desire increase	169		\nFrom fairest creatures we desire increase,\r That thereby beauty’s rose might never die,\r But as the riper should by time decease,\r His tender heir might bear his memory;\r But thou, contracted to thine own bright eyes,\r Feed’st thy light’s flame with self-substantial fuel,\r Making a famine where abundance lies,\r Thyself thy foe, to thy sweet self too cruel.\r Though that art now the world’s fresh ornament\r And only herald to the gaudy spring,\r Within thine own bud buriest thy content,\r And, tender churl, mak’st waste in niggarding.\r    Pity the world, or else this glutton be,\r    To eat the world’s due, by the grave and thee.\n	'1':2 'abund':61 'art':74 'bear':35 'beauti':17 'bright':44 'bud':91 'buriest':92 'churl':97 'content':94 'contract':40 'creatur':5,11 'cruel':71 'deceas':30 'desir':7,13 'die':22 'due':116 'eat':112 'els':107 'eye':45 'fairest':4,10 'famin':59 'feed':46 'flame':51 'foe':65 'fresh':79 'fuel':56 'gaudi':86 'glutton':109 'grave':119 'heir':33 'herald':83 'increas':8,14 'lie':62 'light':49 'mak':98 'make':57 'memori':37 'might':20,34 'never':21 'niggard':102 'ornament':80 'piti':103 'riper':26 'rose':19 'self':54,69 'self-substanti':53 'sonnet':1 'spring':87 'st':47,99 'substanti':55 'sweet':68 'tender':32,96 'thee':121 'therebi':16 'thi':48,64,67,93 'thine':42,89 'thou':39 'though':72 'thyself':63 'time':29 'wast':100 'within':88 'world':77,105,114
348	Sonnet 3: Look in thy glass and tell the face thou viewest	169		\nLook in thy glass and tell the face thou viewest,\r Now is the time that face should form another,\r Whose fresh repair if now thou not renewest,\r Thou dost beguile the world, unbless some mother.\r For where is she so fair whose uneared womb\r Disdains the tillage of thy husbandry?\r Or who is he so fond will be the tomb\r Of his self-love, to stop posterity?\r Thou art thy mother’s glass, and she in thee\r Calls back the lovely April of her prime;\r So thou through windows of thine age shalt see,\r Despite of wrinkles, this thy golden time.\r     But if thou live rememb’red not to be,\r     Die single, and thine image dies with thee.\n	'3':2 'age':105 'anoth':31 'april':95 'art':82 'back':92 'beguil':42 'call':91 'despit':108 'die':124,129 'disdain':57 'dost':41 'face':10,20,28 'fair':53 'fond':68 'form':30 'fresh':33 'glass':6,16,86 'golden':113 'husbandri':62 'imag':128 'live':118 'look':3,13 'love':77,94 'mother':47,84 'poster':80 'prime':98 'red':120 'rememb':119 'renewest':39 'repair':34 'see':107 'self':76 'self-lov':75 'shalt':106 'singl':125 'sonnet':1 'stop':79 'tell':8,18 'thee':90,131 'thi':5,15,61,83,112 'thine':104,127 'thou':11,21,37,40,81,100,117 'tillag':59 'time':26,114 'tomb':72 'unbless':45 'unear':55 'viewest':12,22 'whose':32,54 'window':102 'womb':56 'world':44 'wrinkl':110
397	The Boy’s Answer to the Blackmoor	177		\nBlack maid, complain not that I fly, When Fate commands antipathy: Prodigious might that union prove, Where Night and Day together move, And the conjunction of our lips Not kisses make, but an eclipse, In which the mixed black and white Portends more terror than delight. Yet if my shadow thou wilt be, Enjoy thy dearest wish. But see Thou take my shadow’s property, That hastes away when I come nigh.     Else stay till death hath blinded me, And then I will bequeath myself to thee.\n	'answer':4 'antipathi':18 'away':75 'bequeath':91 'black':8,46 'blackmoor':7 'blind':85 'boy':2 'come':78 'command':17 'complain':10 'conjunct':32 'day':27 'dearest':63 'death':83 'delight':53 'eclips':41 'els':80 'enjoy':61 'fate':16 'fli':14 'hast':74 'hath':84 'kiss':37 'lip':35 'maid':9 'make':38 'might':20 'mix':45 'move':29 'nigh':79 'night':25 'portend':49 'prodigi':19 'properti':72 'prove':23 'see':66 'shadow':57,70 'stay':81 'take':68 'terror':51 'thee':94 'thi':62 'thou':58,67 'till':82 'togeth':28 'union':22 'white':48 'wilt':59 'wish':64 'yet':54
349	Sonnet 35: No more be grieved at that which thou hast done	169		\nNo more be grieved at that which thou hast done:\r Roses have thorns, and silver fountains mud,\r Clouds and eclipses stain both moon and sun,\r And loathsome canker lives in sweetest bud.\r All men make faults, and even I in this,\r Authórizing thy trespass with compare,\r Myself corrupting salving thy amiss,\r Excusing thy sins more than thy sins are:\r For to thy sensual fault I bring in sense—\r Thy adverse party is thy advocate—\r And ‘gainst myself a lawful plea commence.\r Such civil war is in my love and hate,\r    That I an áccessory needs must be\r    To that sweet thief which sourly robs from me.\n	'35':2 'advers':82 'advoc':86 'amiss':63 'authóriz':54 'bring':78 'bud':44 'canker':40 'civil':95 'cloud':30 'commenc':93 'compar':58 'corrupt':60 'done':12,22 'eclips':32 'even':50 'excus':64 'fault':48,76 'fountain':28 'gainst':88 'griev':6,16 'hast':11,21 'hate':102 'law':91 'live':41 'loathsom':39 'love':100 'make':47 'men':46 'moon':35 'mud':29 'must':108 'need':107 'parti':83 'plea':92 'rob':116 'rose':23 'salv':61 'sens':80 'sensual':75 'silver':27 'sin':66,70 'sonnet':1 'sour':115 'stain':33 'sun':37 'sweet':112 'sweetest':43 'thi':55,62,65,69,74,81,85 'thief':113 'thorn':25 'thou':10,20 'trespass':56 'war':96 'áccessori':106
350	Sonnet 65: Since brass, nor stone, nor earth, nor boundless sea	169		\nSince brass, nor stone, nor earth, nor boundless sea\r But sad mortality o’er-sways their power,\r How with this rage shall beauty hold a plea,\r Whose action is no stronger than a flower?\r O, how shall summer’s honey breath hold out\r Against the wrackful siege of batt’ring days,\r When rocks impregnable are not so stout,\r Nor gates of steel so strong, but time decays?\r O fearful meditation! where, alack,\r Shall time’s best jewel from time’s chest lie hid?\r Or what strong hand can hold his swift foot back?\r Or who his spoil of beauty can forbid?\r    O, none, unless this miracle have might,\r    That in black ink my love may still shine bright.\n	'65':2 'action':40 'alack':84 'back':105 'batt':61 'beauti':35,111 'best':88 'black':123 'boundless':10,19 'brass':4,13 'breath':53 'bright':130 'chest':93 'day':63 'decay':79 'earth':8,17 'er':26 'er-sway':25 'fear':81 'flower':46 'foot':104 'forbid':113 'gate':72 'hand':99 'hid':95 'hold':36,54,101 'honey':52 'impregn':66 'ink':124 'jewel':89 'lie':94 'love':126 'may':127 'medit':82 'might':120 'miracl':118 'mortal':23 'none':115 'o':24,47,80,114 'plea':38 'power':29 'rage':33 'ring':62 'rock':65 'sad':22 'sea':11,20 'shall':34,49,85 'shine':129 'sieg':59 'sinc':3,12 'sonnet':1 'spoil':109 'steel':74 'still':128 'stone':6,15 'stout':70 'strong':76,98 'stronger':43 'summer':50 'sway':27 'swift':103 'time':78,86,91 'unless':116 'whose':39 'wrack':58
351	Sonnet 76: Why is my verse so barren of new pride	169		\nWhy is my verse so barren of new pride,\r So far from variation or quick change?\r Why with the time do I not glance aside\r To new-found methods, and to compounds strange?\r Why write I still all one, ever the same,\r And keep invention in a noted weed,\r That every word doth almost tell my name,\r Showing their birth, and where they did proceed?\r O know, sweet love, I always write of you,\r And you and love are still my argument,\r So all my best is dressing old words new,\r Spending again what is already spent:\r    For as the sun is daily new and old,\r    So is my love still telling what is told.\n	'76':2 'almost':66 'alreadi':108 'alway':83 'argument':94 'asid':36 'barren':8,17 'best':98 'birth':72 'chang':27 'compound':44 'daili':115 'doth':65 'dress':100 'ever':52 'everi':63 'far':22 'found':40 'glanc':35 'invent':57 'keep':56 'know':79 'love':81,90,122 'method':41 'name':69 'new':10,19,39,103,116 'new-found':38 'note':60 'o':78 'old':101,118 'one':51 'pride':11,20 'proceed':77 'quick':26 'show':70 'sonnet':1 'spend':104 'spent':109 'still':49,92,123 'strang':45 'sun':113 'sweet':80 'tell':67,124 'time':31 'told':127 'variat':24 'vers':6,15 'weed':61 'word':64,102 'write':47,84
352	Sonnet 87: Farewell! thou art too dear for my possessing	169		\nFarewell! thou art too dear for my possessing,\r And like enough thou knowst thy estimate.\r The Charter of thy worth gives thee releasing;\r My bonds in thee are all determinate.\r For how do I hold thee but by thy granting,\r And for that riches where is my deserving?\r The cause of this fair gift in me is wanting,\r And so my patent back again is swerving.\r Thy self thou gav'st, thy own worth then not knowing,\r Or me, to whom thou gav'st it, else mistaking,\r So thy great gift, upon misprision growing,\r Comes home again, on better judgement making.\r    Thus have I had thee as a dream doth flatter:\r    In sleep a king, but waking no such matter.\n	'87':2 'art':5,13 'back':73 'better':109 'bond':35 'caus':60 'charter':27 'come':105 'dear':7,15 'deserv':58 'determin':40 'doth':120 'dream':119 'els':96 'enough':21 'estim':25 'fair':63 'farewel':3,11 'flatter':121 'gav':80,93 'gift':64,101 'give':31 'grant':50 'great':100 'grow':104 'hold':45 'home':106 'judgement':110 'king':125 'know':87 'knowst':23 'like':20 'make':111 'matter':130 'mispris':103 'mistak':97 'patent':72 'possess':10,18 'releas':33 'rich':54 'self':78 'sleep':123 'sonnet':1 'st':81,94 'swerv':76 'thee':32,37,46,116 'thi':24,29,49,77,82,99 'thou':4,12,22,79,92 'thus':112 'upon':102 'wake':127 'want':68 'worth':30,84
