412	Upon My Lady Carlisle’s Walking in Hampton Court Garden	181		\nDIALOGUE\r        T.C.       J.S.\rThom. Didst thou not find the place inspired,\rAnd flowers, as if they had desired\rNo other sun, start from their beds,\rAnd for a sight steal out their heads?\rHeardst thou not music when she talked?\rAnd didst not find that as she walked\rShe threw rare perfumes all about,\rSuch as bean-blossoms newly out,\rOr chafèd spices give?—\rJ.S. I must confess those perfumes, Tom,\rI did not smell; nor found that from\rHer passing by ought sprung up new.\rThe flowers had all their birth from you;\rFor I passed o’er the self-same walk\rAnd did not find one single stalk\rOf anything that was to bring\rThis unknown after-after-spring.\rThom. Dull and insensible, couldst see\rA thing so near a deity\rMove up and down, and feel no change?\rJ.S. None, and so great, were alike strange;\rI had my thoughts, but not your way.\rAll are not born, sir, to the bay.\rAlas! Tom, I am flesh and blood,\rAnd was consulting how I could\rIn spite of masks and hoods descry\rThe parts denied unto the eye.\rI was undoing all she wore,\rAnd had she walked but one turn more,\rEve in her first state had not been\rMore naked or more plainly seen.\rThom. ’Twas well for thee she left the place;\rThere is great danger in that face.\rBut hadst thou viewed her leg and thigh,\rAnd upon that discovery\rSearched after parts that are more dear\r(As fancy seldom stops so near),\rNo time or age had ever seen\rSo lost a thing as thou hadst been.\n	'after-after-spr':131 'age':277 'ala':179 'alik':161 'anyth':124 'bay':178 'bean':68 'bean-blossom':67 'bed':35 'birth':103 'blood':185 'blossom':69 'born':174 'bring':128 'carlisl':4 'chafèd':73 'chang':154 'confess':79 'consult':188 'could':191 'couldst':139 'court':9 'danger':245 'dear':267 'deiti':146 'deni':201 'descri':198 'desir':28 'dialogu':11 'didst':15,52 'discoveri':260 'dull':136 'er':110 'eve':219 'ever':279 'eye':204 'face':248 'fanci':269 'feel':152 'f