449	Medley of the Cut	107		\nThe column of the commander yielded to our first sweep.\rEven the water jar for our diggers we set on the south wall\rof the general’s tomb without knowing it. So we began.\rHis armies retook Nubia, Libya, and the Levant,\rlost under the sway-bellied lantern-jawed Sun King.\rOverseer of all scribes, Overseer of the priests of Horus,\rGrain-giver to all lands, Royal chief of staff, Regent,\rthe general had himself carried on his palanquin\rthrough the wailing processions\rto oversee the work on this place. And so carved, thus:\rone of his men punches a Nubian in the face.\rThe general was low-born; everything had counted\rand he knew what counted most.\rHis platoons lift open palms towards Tutankhamun.\rThe general towers as a sway-girdled go-between at court\rfor beseeching Libyans.\rOnly the pearl-handled revolvers do not figure here,\ror the comeback challenge Nuts! in the Ardennes winter forest.\rHe had himself carried beyond the busy streets of the dead\rin the city of the dead sloping back from the bluff\rto a higher, private terrace looking across to Memphis.\rBut then he rose to Pharaoh. So he is not here. Instead\rhis first wife lay here, and then his queen also.\rAt his own royal tomb in the Valley, where the designs\rremained uncarved, sketching idea along stone,\rhe does not rest either. The fine picklock hand\rgot past Anubis and the reared serpents, and got to him,\rthe Lord of Upper and Lower Egypt. It got past Truth\rwith her high feather, which moved at the slightest disturbance.\rThe general did deep obeisance to her. He is not here.\rWhat at last moves the heart?\rSo much already moved, even in his own century,\rarchitects prying loose mud bricks of the core for new tombs.\rCult funded in perpetuity gone in two generations.\rSo Coleridge, who was indisposed that day, prudently\rremained in the circle of lime trees while his friends went off\ron their walk through the countryside. He followed them in his mind.\rThat way no one would have to dismantle Horeheb’s outer court\rto secure bricks for the statuary room, and facing stones.\rHe cast his mind outward, a net over his dear ones,\rsending them at pace through the middle distance of steeples,\rhill lines, and the murder of Lamb’s mother by his sister,\ra brief madness, thus through the appropriately middle distance\rwhere such things are built and performed in fact, no closer, no farther,\rthen on out to the cleansing rim of apocalypse, evening\rin the bath of waning fire, one bird stitching\rthe whole veil of showings tight along its upper hem—\rthough he was not there, he could tell them that none the less\rhe was next to his words and his word was with them, even\runto the rim of their wandering and their turning back.\rOne dome of air and fire. But he was not there. Nor I here.\rWhat removes the heart from what moves it?\rAs if I were the lecturer before a congress of doctors,\rhis clinching point approaching, when suddenly he stared out\rin silence, and at last said, Ladies and gentlemen, esteemed colleagues,\rthe only thing I can see at this moment inside my brain,\rsuch as it is, is a little white mouse chasing a little white ball.	'across':198 'air':503 'along':238,460 'alreadi':300 'also':222 'anubi':251 'apocalyps':443 'approach':536 'appropri':419 'architect':307 'ardenn':167 'armi':40 'back':188,499 'ball':578 'bath':447 'began':38 'belli':52 'beseech':148 'beyond':174 'bird':452 'bluff':191 'born':117 'brain':564 'brick':311,372 'brief':414 'built':426 'busi':176 'carri':83,173 'carv':100 'cast':381 'centuri':306 'challeng':163 'chase':574 'chief':75 'circl':337 'citi':183 'cleans':440 'clinch':534 'closer':432 'coleridg':327 'colleagu':552 'column':6 'comeback':162 'command':9 'congress':530 'core':314 'could':470 'count':120,125 'countrysid':351 'court':146,369 'cult':318 'cut':4 'day':332 'dead':180,186 'dear':389 'deep':284 'design':233 'digger':21 'dismantl':365 'distanc':398,421 'disturb':280 'doctor':532 'dome