457	After Death	206		\nThe curtains were half drawn, the floor was swept\r   And strewn with rushes, rosemary and may\rLay thick upon the bed on which I lay,\rWhere through the lattice ivy-shadows crept.\rHe leaned above me, thinking that I slept\r   And could not hear him; but I heard him say,\r   ‘Poor child, poor child’: and as he turned away\rCame a deep silence, and I knew he wept.\rHe did not touch the shroud, or raise the fold\r   That hid my face, or take my hand in his,\r      Or ruffle the smooth pillows for my head:\r      He did not love me living; but once dead\r   He pitied me; and very sweet it is\rTo know he still is warm though I am cold.\r\n	'away':62 'bed':23 'came':63 'child':55,57 'cold':126 'could':45 'crept':35 'curtain':4 'dead':108 'death':2 'deep':65 'drawn':7 'face':85 'floor':9 'fold':81 'half':6 'hand':89 'head':99 'hear':47 'heard':51 'hid':83 'ivi':33 'ivy-shadow':32 'knew':69 'know':118 'lattic':31 'lay':19,27 'lean':37 'live':105 'love':103 'may':18 'pillow':96 'piti':110 'poor':54,56 'rais':79 'rosemari':16 'ruffl':93 'rush':15 'say':53 'shadow':34 'shroud':77 'silenc':66 'slept':43 'smooth':95 'still':120 'strewn':13 'sweet':114 'swept':11 'take':87 'thick':20 'think':40 'though':123 'touch':75 'turn':61 'upon':21 'warm':122 'wept':71
