514	To J.G. On the News of His Marriage	238		\nMy Love? alas! I must not call you Mine,\rBut to your envy’d Bride that Name resign:\rI must forget your lovely melting Charms,\rAnd be for ever Banisht from your Arms:\rFor ever? oh! the Horror of that Sound!\rIt gives my bleeding Heart a deadly wound:\rWhile I might hope, although my Hope was vain,\rIt gave some Ease to my unpitty’d Pain,\rBut now your Hymen doth all Hope exclude,\rAnd but to think is Sin; yet you intrude\rOn every Thought; if I but close my Eyes,\rMethinks your pleasing Form besides me lies;\rWith every Sigh I gently breath your Name,\rYet no ill Thoughts pollute my hallow’d Flame;\r’Tis pure and harmless, as a Lambent Fire,\rAnd never mingled with a warm Desire:\rAll I have now to ask of Bounteous Heaven,\rIs, that your Perjuries may be forgiven:\rThat she who you have with your Nuptials blest,\rAs She’s the Happiest Wife, may prove the Best:\rThat all our Joys may light on you alone,\rThen I can be contented to have none:\rAnd never wish that you shou’d kinder be,\rThan now and then, to cast a Thought on Me:\rAnd, Madam, though the Conquest you have won,\rOver my Strephon, has my hopes undone;\rI’le daily beg of Heaven, he may be\rKinder to You, than he has been to Me.\r\n	'ala':11 'alon':184 'although':62 'arm':41 'ask':146 'banisht':38 'beg':230 'besid':106 'best':175 'bleed':53 'blest':165 'bounteous':148 'breath':114 'bride':23 'call':15 'cast':207 'charm':33 'close':99 'conquest':216 'content':189 'd':22,74,124,199 'daili':229 'dead':56 'desir':140 'doth':80 'eas':70 'envi':21 'ever':37,43 'everi':94,110 'exclud':83 'eye':101 'fire':133 'flame':125 'forget':29 'forgiven':156 'form':105 'gave':68 'gentl':113 'give':51 'hallow':123 'happiest':170 'harmless':129 'heart':54 'heaven':149,232 'hope':61,64,82,225 'horror':46 'hymen':79 'ill':119 'intrud':92 'j.g':2 'joy':179 'kinder':200,236 'lambent':132 'le':228 'lie':108 'light':181 'love':10,31 'madam':213 'marriag':8 'may':154,172,180,234 'melt'