518	When Last We Parted	240		\nWhen last we parted, thou wert young and fair,\r   How beautiful let fond remembrance say!\r   Alas! since then old time has stolen away\rFull thirty years, leaving my temples bare.—\rSo has it perished like a thing of air,\r   The dream of love and youth!— now both are grey\r   Yet still remembering that delightful day,\rThough time with his cold touch has blanched my hair,\r   Though I have suffered many years of pain\rSince then, though I did never think to live\r   To hear that voice or see those eyes again,\rI can a sad but cordial greeting give,\rAnd for thy welfare breathe as warm a prayer—\rAs when I loved thee young and fair.\r\n	'air':43 'ala':20 'away':27 'bare':34 'beauti':15 'blanch':67 'breath':108 'cold':64 'cordial':101 'day':59 'delight':58 'dream':45 'eye':94 'fair':13,120 'fond':17 'full':28 'give':103 'greet':102 'grey':53 'hair':69 'hear':88 'last':2,6 'leav':31 'let':16 'like':39 'live':86 'love':47,116 'mani':74 'never':83 'old':23 'pain':77 'part':4,8 'perish':38 'prayer':112 'rememb':56 'remembr':18 'sad':99 'say':19 'see':92 'sinc':21,78 'still':55 'stolen':26 'suffer':73 'templ':33 'thee':117 'thi':106 'thing':41 'think':84 'thirti':29 'thou':9 'though':60,70,80 'time':24,61 'touch':65 'voic':90 'warm':110 'welfar':107 'wert':10 'year':30,75 'yet':54 'young':11,118 'youth':49
519	A Song	241		\nLove, thou art best of Human Joys,\r   Our chiefest Happiness below;\rAll other Pleasures are but Toys,\rMusick without Thee is but Noise,\r     And Beauty but an empty show.\rHeav’n , who knew best what Man wou’d move,\r   And raise his Thoughts above the Brute;\rSaid, Let him Be, and Let him Love;\rThat must alone his Soul improve,\r     Howe’er Philosophers dispute.\r\n	'alon':59 'art':5 'beauti':27 'best':6,36 'brute':48 'chiefest':11 'd':40 'disput':66 'empti':30 'er':64 'happi':12 'heav':32 'howe':63 'human':8 'improv':62 'joy':9 'knew':35 'let':50,54 'love':3,56 'man':38 'move':41 'musick':20 'must':58 'n':33 'nois':25 'philosoph':65 'pleasur':16 'rais':43 'said':49 'show':31 'song':2 'soul':61 'thee':22 'thou':4 'thought':45 'toy':19 'without':21 'wou':39
520	A Letter to Daphnis	241		\nThis to the crown and blessing of my life,\rThe much loved husband of a happy wife;\rTo him whose constant passion found the art\rTo win a stubborn and ungrateful heart,\rAnd to the world by tenderest proof discovers\rThey err, who say that husbands can’t be lovers.\rWith such return of passion as is due,\rDaphnis I love, Daphnis my thoughts pursue;\rDaphnis my hopes and joys are bounded all in you.\rEven I, for Daphnis’ and my promise’ sake,\rWhat I in women censure, undertake.\rBut this from love, not vanity, proceeds;\rYou know who writes, and I who ’tis that reads.\rJudge not my passion by my want of skill:\rMany love well, though they express it ill;\rAnd I your censure could with pleasure bear,\rWould you but soon return, and speak it here.\r\n	'art':29 'bear':135 'bless':10 'bound':76 'censur':92,131 'constant':25 'could':132 'crown':8 'daphni':4,63,66,70,83 'discov':44 'due':62 'err':46 'even':80 'express':125 'found':27 'happi':20 'heart':36 'hope':72 'husband':17,50 'ill':127 'joy':74 'judg':111 'know':102 'letter':2 'life':13 'love':16,65,97,121 'lover':54 'mani':120 'much':15 'passion':26,59,114 'pleasur':134 'proceed':100 'promis':86 'proof':43 'pursu':69 'read':110 'return':57,140 'sake':87 'say':48 'skill':119 'soon':139 'speak':142 'stubborn':33 'tenderest':42 'though':123 'thought':68 'tis':108 'undertak':93 'ungrat':35 'vaniti':99 'want':117 'well':122 'whose':24 'wife':21 'win':31 'women':91 'world':40 'would':136 'write':104
521	The Unfortunate Damsel	242		\nI sowed the seeds of love\rTo blossom all the spring,\rIn April, May, or else in June,\rWhen the small birds do sing:\rA gardener standing by,\rI desired him to choose for me;\rHe picked out the lily, the violet, and pink,\rBut I refused all three.\rThe lily I refused,\rBecause it faded so soon;\rThe violet and pink I overlooked,\rResolved was to tarry till June:\rIn June the red roses bud,\rOh, that is a lover for me;\rBut I have often aimed at the red rose-bud,\rAnd I have gained the willow tree.\rThe gardener standing by,\rHe prayed me to have a care,\rFor the thorn that grew on the red rose-bush,\rA venomous thorn they were:\rA venomous thorn indeed,\rFor still I feel the smart;\rAnd every time I did it touch,\rIt pricked my tender heart.\rAway you fading flowers,\rNo more I will you touch,\rThat all the world may plainly see\rI loved one flower too much.\r\n	'aim':91 'april':16 'away':154 'bird':25 'blossom':11 'bud':79,97 'bush':126 'care':115 'choos':36 'damsel':3 'desir':33 'els':19 'everi':143 'fade':59,156 'feel':139 'flower':157,174 'gain':101 'garden':29,106 'grew':120 'heart':153 'inde':135 'june':21,73,75 'lili':43,54 'love':9,172 'lover':84 'may':17,168 'much':176 'often':90 'oh':80 'one':173 'overlook':67 'pick':40 'pink':47,65 'plain':169 'pray':110 'prick':150 'red':77,94,123 'refus':50,56 'resolv':68 'rose':78,96,125 'rose-bud':95 'rose-bush':124 'see':170 'seed':7 'sing':27 'small':24 'smart':141 'soon':61 'sow':5 'spring':14 'stand':30,107 'still':137 'tarri':71 'tender':152 'thorn':118,129,134 'three':52 'till':72 'time':144 'touch':148,163 'tree':104 'unfortun':2 'venom':128,133 'violet':45,63 'willow':103 'world':167
522	Alexandreis	243		\nI sing the man that never equal knew, Whose mighty arms all Asia did subdue, Whose conquests through the spacious world do ring, That city-raser, king-destroying king, Who o’er the warlike Macedons did reign, And worthily the name of Great did gain. This is the prince (if fame you will believe, To ancient story any credit give.) Who when the globe of Earth he had subdued, With tears the easy victory pursued; Because that no more worlds there were to win, No further scene to act his glories in.     Ah that some pitying Muse would now inspire My frozen style with a poetic fire, And raptures worthy of his matchless fame, Whose deeds I sing, whose never fading name Long as the world shall fresh and deathless last, No less to future ages, then the past. Great my presumption is, I must confess, But if I thrive, my glory’s ne’er the less; Nor will it from his conquests derogate A female pen his acts did celebrate. If thou O Muse wilt thy assistance give, Such as made Naso and great Maro live, With him whom Melas’ fertile banks did bear, Live, though their bodies dust and ashes are; Whose laurels were not fresher, than their fame Is now, and will for ever be the same. If the like favor thou wilt grant to me, O Queen of Verse, I’ll not ungrateful be, My choicest hours to thee I’ll dedicate, ’Tis thou shalt rule, ’tis thou shalt be my fate. But if coy goddess thou shalt this deny, And from my humble suit disdaining fly, I’ll stoop and beg no more, since I know this, Writing of him, I cannot write amiss: His lofty deeds will raise each feeble line, And god-like acts will make my verse divine.     ’Twas at the time the golden sun doth rise, And with his beams enlights the azure skies, When lo a troop in silver arms drew near, The glorious sun did nere so bright appear; Dire scarlet plumes adorned their haughty crests, And crescent shields did shade their shining breasts; Down from their shoulders hung a panther’s hide, A bow and quiver rattled by their side; Their hands a knotty well tried spear did bear, Jocund they seemed, and quite devoid of fear. These warlike virgins were, that do reside   Near Thermodon’s smooth banks and verdant side, The plains of Themiscyre their birth do boast, Thalestris now did head the beauteous host; She emulating that illustrious dame, Who to the aid of Troy and Priam came, And her who the Retulian prince did aid, Though dearly both for their assistance paid. But fear she scorned, nor the like fate did dread, Her host she often to the field had led, As oft in triumph had returned again, Glory she only sought for all her pain.     This martial queen had heard how loudly fame, Echoed our conqueror’s redoubted name, Her soul his conduct and his courage fired, To see the hero she so much admired; And to Hyrcania for this cause she went, Where Alexander (wholly then intent On triumphs and such military sport) At truce with war held both his camp and court. And while before the town she did attend Her messengers return, she saw ascend A cloud of dust, that covered all the sky, And still at every pause there stroke her eye. The interrupted beams of burnished gold, As dust the splendor hid, or did unfold; Loud neighings of the steeds, and trumpets’ sound Filled all the air, and echoed from the ground; The gallant Greeks with a brisk march drew near, And their great chief did at their head appear. And now come up to th’Amazonian band, They made a halt and a respectful stand: And both the troops (with like amazement strook) Did each on other with deep silence look. Th’heroic queen (whose high pretence to war Cancelled the bashful laws and nicer bar Of modesty, which did her sex restrain) First boldly did advance before her train, And thus she spake. All but a god in name, And that a debt time owes unto thy fame.          This was the first essay of this young lady in          poetry, but finding the task she had undertaken          hard, she laid it by till practice and more time          should make her equal to so great a work.	'act':92,172,305 'admir':516 'adorn':348 'advanc':684 'age':139 'ah':96 'aid':432,445 'air':603 'alexand':526 'alexandrei':1 'amaz':649 'amazonian':633 'amiss':292 'ancient':59 'appear':344,626 'arm':12,334 'ascend':559 'ash':205 'asia':14 'assist':181,451 'attend':553 'azur':326 'band':634 'bank':196,405 'bar':673 'bash':669 'beam':323,580 'bear':198,385 'beauteous':422 'beg':279 'believ':57 'birth':414 'boast':416 'bodi':202 'bold':682 'bow':370 'breast':359 'bright':343 'brisk':614 'burnish':582 'came':437 'camp':543 'cancel':667 'cannot':290 'caus':522 'celebr':174 'chief':621 'choicest':243 'citi':27 'city-ras':26 'cloud':561 'come':629 'conduct':504 'confess':149 'conqueror':497 'conquest':18,166 'courag':507 'court':545 'cover':565 'coy':262 'credit':62 'crescent':353 'crest':351 'dame':428 'dear':447 'deathless':133 'debt':701 'dedic':249 'deed':119,295 'deep':656 'deni':267 'derog':167 'destroy':31 'devoid':391 'dire':345 'disdain':273 'divin':310 'doth':318 'dread':462 'drew':335,616 'dust':203,563,585 'earth':69 'easi':76 'echo':495,605 'emul':425 'enlight':324 'equal':8,738 'er':35,158 'essay':711 'ever':220 'everi':572 'eye':577 'fade':124 'fame':54,117,214,494,706 'fate':259,460 'favor':227 'fear':393,454 'feebl':299 'femal':169 'fertil':195 'field':469 'fill':600 'find':719 'fire':110,508 'first':681,710 'fli':274 'fresh':131 'fresher':211 'frozen':105 'futur':138 'gain':48 'gallant':610 'give':63,182 'globe':67 'glori':94,155,479 'glorious':338 'god':303,695 'god-lik':302 'goddess':263 'gold':583 'golden':316 'grant':230 'great':46,143,188,620,741 'greek':611 'ground':608 'halt':638 'hand':378 'hard':725 'haughti':350 'head':420,625 'heard':491 'held':540 'hero':512 'heroic':660 'hid':588 'hide':368 'high':663 'host':423,464 'hour':244 'humbl':271 'hung':364 'hyrcania':519 'illustri':427 'inspir':103 'intent':529 'interrupt':579 'jocund':386 'king':30,32 'king-destroy':29 'knew':9 'knotti':380 'know':284 'ladi':71