523	The Introduction	241		\nDid I, my lines intend for public view,\rHow many censures, would their faults pursue,\rSome would, because such words they do affect,\rCry they’re insipid, empty, and uncorrect.\rAnd many have attained, dull and untaught,\rThe name of wit only by finding fault.\rTrue judges might condemn their want of wit,\rAnd all might say, they’re by a woman writ.\rAlas! a woman that attempts the pen,\rSuch an intruder on the rights of men,\rSuch a presumptuous creature, is esteemed,\rThe fault can by no virtue be redeemed.\rThey tell us we mistake our sex and way;\rGood breeding, fashion, dancing, dressing, play\rAre the accomplishments we should desire;\rTo write, or read, or think, or to inquire\rWould cloud our beauty, and exhaust our time,\rAnd interrupt the conquests of our prime;\rWhilst the dull manage of a servile house\rIs held by some our outmost art, and use.\r   Sure ’twas not ever thus, nor are we told\rFables, of women that excelled of old;\rTo whom, by the diffusive hand of Heaven \rSome share of wit, and poetry was given.\rOn that glad day, on which the Ark returned,\rThe holy pledge, for which the land had mourned,\rThe joyful tribes, attend it on the way,\rThe Levites do the sacred charge convey,\rWhilst various instruments, before it play;\rHere, holy virgins in the concert join\rThe louder notes, to soften, and refine,\rAnd with alternate verse complete the hymn divine.\rLo! the young Poet, after God’s own heart,\rBy Him inspired, and taught the Muses’ art,\rReturned from conquest, a bright chorus meets,\rThat sing his slain ten thousand in the streets.\rIn such loud numbers they his acts declare,\rProclaim the wonders of his early war,\rThat Saul upon the vast applause does frown,\rAnd feels its mighty thunder shake the crown.\rWhat, can the threatened judgment now prolong?\rHalf of the kingdom is already gone;\rThe fairest half, whose influence guides the rest,\rHave David’s empire o’er their hearts confessed.\r   A woman here, leads fainting Israel on,\rShe fights, she wins, she triumphs with a song,\rDevout, majestic, for the subject fit,\rAnd far above her arms, exalts her wit;\rThen, to the peaceful, shady palm withdraws,\rAnd rules the rescued nation, with her laws.\rHow are we fall’n, fall’n by mistaken rules?\rAnd education’s, more than nature’s fools,\rDebarred from all improvements of the mind,\rAnd to be dull, expected and designed;\rAnd if some one would soar above the rest,\rWith warmer fancy, and ambition pressed,\rSo strong th’ opposing faction still appears,\rThe hopes to thrive can ne’er outweigh the fears,\rBe cautioned then my Muse, and still retired;\rNor be despised, aiming to be admired;\rConscious of wants, still with contracted wing,\rTo some few friends, and to thy sorrows sing;\rFor groves of laurel thou wert never meant;\rBe dark enough thy shades, and be thou there content.\n	'accomplish':112 'act':289 'admir':468 'affect':25 'aim':465 'ala':66 'alreadi':326 'altern':244 'ambit':435 'appear':443 'applaus':303 'ark':196 'arm':371 'art':154,266 'attain':36 'attempt':70 'attend':210 'beauti':128 'breed':105 'bright':271 'caution':455 'censur':13 'charg':220 'chorus':272 'cloud':126 'complet':246 'concert':233 'condemn':51 'confess':344 'conquest':136,269 'conscious':469 'content':502 'contract':474 'convey':221 'creatur':84 'cri':26 'crown':313 'danc':107 'dark':494 'david':337 'day':192 'debar':408 'declar':290 'design':421 'desir':115 'despis':464 'devout':361 'diffus':177 'divin':249 'dress':108 'dull':37,142,418 'earli':296 'educ':401 'empir':339 'empti':30 'enough':495 'er':341,450 'esteem':86 'ever':160 'exalt':372 'excel':170 'exhaust':130 'expect':419 'fabl':166 'faction':441 'faint':349 'fairest':329 'fall':393,395 'fanci':433 'far':368 'fashion':106 'fault':16,47,88 'fear':453 'feel':307 'fight':353 'find':46 'fit':366 'fool':407 'friend':479 'frown':305 'given':188 'glad':191 'god':255 'gone':327 'good':104 'grove':486 'guid':333 'half':321,330 'hand':178