524	The Spleen	241		\nWhat art thou, Spleen, which ev’ry thing dost ape?\r  Thou Proteus to abused mankind,\r  Who never yet thy real cause could find,\rOr fix thee to remain in one continued shape.\r  Still varying thy perplexing form,\r  Now a Dead Sea thou’lt represent,\r  A calm of stupid discontent,\rThen, dashing on the rocks wilt rage into a storm.\r  Trembling sometimes thou dost appear,\r  Dissolved into a panic fear;\r  On sleep intruding dost thy shadows spread,\r  Thy gloomy terrors round the silent bed,\rAnd crowd with boding dreams the melancholy head;\r  Or, when the midnight hour is told,\r  And drooping lids thou still dost waking hold,\r  Thy fond delusions cheat the eyes,\r  Before them antic specters dance,\rUnusual fires their pointed heads advance,\r  And airy phantoms rise.\r  Such was the monstrous vision seen,\rWhen Brutus (now beneath his cares opprest,\rAnd all Rome’s fortunes rolling in his breast,\r  Before Philippi’s latest field,\rBefore his fate did to Octavius lead)\r  Was vanquished by the Spleen.\r  Falsely, the mortal part we blame\r  Or our depressed, and pond’rous frame,\r  Which, till the first degrading sin\r  Let thee, its dull attendant, in,\r  Still with the other did comply,\rNor clogged the active soul, disposed to fly,\rAnd range the mansions of its native sky.\r  Nor, whilst in his own heaven he dwelt,\r  Whilst Man his paradise possessed,\rHis fertile Garden in the fragrant East,\r  And all united odors smelled,\r  No armèd sweets, until thy reign,\r  Could shock the sense, or in the face\r  A flushed, unhandsome color place.\rNow the jonquil o’ercomes the feeble brain;\rWe faint beneath the aromatic pain,\rTill some offensive scent thy pow’rs appease,\rAnd pleasure we resign for short and nauseous ease.\r  In ev’ry one thou dost possess,\r  New are thy motions, and thy dress:\r  Now in some grove a list’ning friend\r  Thy false suggestions must attend,\rThy whispered griefs, thy fancied sorrows hear,\rBreathed in a sigh, and witnessed by a tear;\r  Whilst in the light and vulgar crowd,\r  Thy slaves, more clamorous and loud,\rBy laughters unprovoked, thy influence too confess.\rIn the imperious wife thou vapors art,\r  Which from o’erheated passions rise\r  In clouds to the attractive brain,\r  Until descending thence again,\r  Through the o’er-cast and show’ring eyes,\r  Upon her husband’s softened heart,\r  He the disputed point must yield,\rSomething resign of the contested field;\rTill lordly Man, born to imperial sway,\rCompounds for peace, to make that right away,\rAnd Woman, arm’d with Spleen, does servilely obey.\r  The fool, to imitate the wits,\r  Complains of thy pretended fits,\r  And dullness, born with him, would lay\r  Upon thy accidental sway;\r  Because, sometimes, thou dost presume\r  Into the ablest heads to come:\r  That, often, men of thoughts refined,\r  Impatient of unequal sense,\rSuch slow returns, where they so much dispense,\rRetiring from the crowd, are to thy shades inclined.\r  O’er me alas! thou dost too much prevail:\r  I feel thy force, whilst I against thee rail;\rI feel my verse decay, and my cramped numbers fail.\rThrough thy black jaundice I all objects see,\r  As dark and terrible as thee,\rMy lines decried, and my employment thought\rAn useless folly, or presumptuous fault:\r  Whilst in the Muses’ paths I stray,\rWhilst in their groves, and by their secret springs\rMy hand delights to trace unusual things,\rAnd deviates from the known and common way;\r  Nor will in fading silks compose  \r  Faintly th’ inimitable rose,\rFill up an ill-drawn bird, or paint on glass\rThe sov’reign’s blurred and undistinguished face,\rThe threat’ning angel, and the speaking ass.\r  Patron thou art to ev’ry gross abuse,\r       The sullen husband’s feigned excuse, \rWhen the ill humor with his wife he spends,\rAnd bears recruited wit, and spirits to his friends.\r       The son of Bacchus pleads thy pow’r,\r       As to the glass he still repairs,\r       Pretends but to remove thy cares,\rSnatch from thy shades one gay and smiling hour,\rAnd drown thy kingdom in a purple show’r.\rWhen the Coquette, whom ev’ry fool admires,\r       Would in variety be fair,\r       And, changing hastily the scene,\r       From light, impertinent, and vain,\rAssumes a soft, a melancholy air,\rAnd of her eyes rebates the wand’ring fires,\rThe careless posture, and the head reclined,\r       The thoughtful, and composèd face,\r  Proclaiming the withdrawn, the absent mind,\r  Allows the Fop more liberty to gaze,\r  Who gently for the tender cause inquires;\r  The cause, indeed, is a defect in sense,\rYet is the Spleen alleged, and still the dull pretence.\r       But these are thy fantastic harms, \r       The tricks of thy pernicious stage,\r       Which do the weaker sort engage;\r  Worse are the dire effects of thy more pow’rful charms.\r       By thee Religion, all we know,\r       That should enlighten here below,\r       Is veiled in darkness, and perplexed\r  With anxious doubts, with endless scruples vexed,\rAnd some restraint implied from each perverted text.\r  Whilst touch not, taste not, what is freely giv’n,\rIs but thy niggard voice, disgracing bounteous heav’n.\r  From speech restrained, by thy deceits abused,\r  To deserts banished, or in cells reclused,\r  Mistaken vot’ries to the pow’rs divine,\r  Whilst they a purer sacrifice design,\rDo but the Spleen obey, and worship at thy shrine.\r  In vain to chase thee ev’ry art we try,\r       In vain all remedies apply,\r       In vain the Indian leaf infuse,\r       Or the parched Eastern berry bruise;\rSome pass, in vain, those bounds, and nobler liquors use.\r       Now harmony, in vain, we bring,\r       Inspire the flute, and touch the string.\r       From harmony no help is had;\rMusic but soothes thee, if too sweetly sad,\rAnd if too light, but turns thee gaily mad.\r       Though the physicians greatest gains,\r       Although his growing wealth he sees\r       Daily increased by ladies’ fees,\r  Yet dost thou baffle all his studious pains.\r       Not skillful Lower thy source could find,\r  Or through the well-dissected body trace\r       The secret, the mysterious ways,\rBy which thou dost surprise, and prey upon the mind.\rThough in the search, too deep for humane thought,\r  With unsuccessful toil he wrought,\r’Till thinking thee to’ve catched, himself by thee was caught,\r  Retained thy pris’ner, thy acknowledged slave,\rAnd sunk beneath thy chain to a lamented grave.\n	'ablest':458 'absent':737 'abus':16,619,857 'accident':449 'acknowledg':1046 'activ':203 'admir':690 'advanc':125 'air':711 'airi':127 'ala':492 'alleg':765 'allow':739 'although':967 'angel':607 'antic':117 'anxious':818 'ape':12 'appear':66 'appeas':281 'appli':903 'arm':422 'armèd':242 'aromat':272 'art':4,360,614,896 'ass':611 'assum':706 'attend':192,317 'attract':371 'away':419 'bacchus':647 'baffl':981 'banish':860 'bear':636 'bed':85 'beneath':139,270,1050 'berri':914 'bird':591 'black':519 'blame':174 'blur':600 'bode':89 'bodi':999 'born':408,442 'bound':921 'bounteous':848 'brain':267,372 'breast':151 'breath':325 'bring':931 'bruis':915 'brutus':137 'calm':48 'care':141,664 'careless':722 'cast':382 'catch':1035 'caught':1040 'caus':23,751,754 'cell':863 'chain':1052 'chang':697 'charm':799 'chase':892 'cheat':112 'clamor':344 'clog':201 'cloud':368 'color':258 'come':461 'common':573 'complain':435 'compli':199 'compos':580 'composèd':731 'compound':412 'confess':353 'contest':403 'continu':33 'coquett':685 'could':24,247,991 'cramp':514 'crowd':87,340,483 'd':423 'daili':973 'danc':119 'dark':526,814 'dash':53 'dead':42 'decay':511 'deceit':856 'decri':533 'deep':1021 'defect':758 'degrad':186 'delight':562 'delus':111 'depress':177 'descend':374 'desert':859 'design':878 'deviat':568 'dire':792 'discont':51 'disgrac':847 'dispens':479 'dispos':205 'disput':395 'dissect':998 'dissolv':67 'divin':872 'dost':11,65,75,106,296,454,494,979,1009 'doubt':8