592	The Elements of San Joaquin	262		\nField The wind sprays pale dirt into my mouth \rThe small, almost invisible scars \rOn my hands.\rThe pores in my throat and elbows\rHave taken in a seed of dirt of their own.\rAfter a day in the grape fields near Rolinda \rA fine silt, washed by sweat, \rHas settled into the lines \rOn my wrists and palms.\rAlready I am becoming the valley, \rA soil that sprouts nothing. \rFor any of us.\rWind A dry wind over the valley\rPeeled mountains, grain by grain, \rTo small slopes, loose dirt\rWhere red ants tunnel.\rThe wind strokes\rThe skulls and spines of cattle \rTo white dust, to nothing,\rCovers the spiked tracks of beetles, \rOf tumbleweed, of sparrows \rThat pecked the ground for insects.\rEvenings, when I am in the yard weeding, \rThe wind picks up the breath of my armpits\rLike dust, swirls it \rMiles away\rAnd drops it\rOn the ear of a rabid dog, \rAnd I take on another life.\rWind When you got up this morning the sun \rBlazed an hour in the sky,\rA lizard hid\rUnder the curled leaves of manzanita \rAnd winked its dark lids.\rLater, the sky grayed,\rAnd the cold wind you breathed\rWas moving under your skin and already far \rFrom the small hives of your lungs.\rStars At dusk the first stars appear.\rNot one eager finger points toward them. \rA little later the stars spread with the night \rAnd an orange moon rises\rTo lead them, like a shepherd, toward dawn.\rSun In June the sun is a bonnet of light \rComing up,\rLittle by little,\rFrom behind a skyline of pine.\rThe pastures sway with fiddle-neck, \rTassels of foxtail.\rAt Piedra\rA couple fish on the river’s edge, \rTheir shadows deep against the water. \rAbove, in the stubbled slopes,\rCows climb down\rAs the heat rises\rIn a mist of blond locusts,\rReturning to the valley.\rRain When autumn rains flatten sycamore leaves, \rThe tiny volcanos of dirt\rAnts raised around their holes,\rI should be out of work.\rMy silverware and stack of plates will go unused \rLike the old, my two good slacks\rWill smother under a growth of lint\rAnd smell of the old dust\rThat rises\rWhen the closet door opens or closes.\rThe skin of my belly will tighten like a belt \rAnd there will be no reason for pockets.\rHarvest East of the sun’s slant, in the vineyard that never failed, \rA wind crossed my face, moving the dust \rAnd a portion of my voice a step closer to a new year.\rThe sky went black in the ninth hour of rolling trays, \rAnd in the distance ropes of rain dropped to pull me \rFrom the thick harvest that was not mine.\rFog If you go to your window\rYou will notice a fog drifting in.\rThe sun is no stronger than a flashlight. \rNot all the sweaters \rHung in closets all summer\rCould soak up this mist. The fog:\rA mouth nibbling everything to its origin, \rPomegranate trees, stolen bicycles,\rThe string of lights at a used-car lot, \rA Pontiac with scorched valves.\rIn Fresno the fog is passing\rThe young thief prying a window screen, \rGraying my hair that falls\rAnd goes unfound, my fingerprints \rSlowly growing a fur of dust\rOne hundred years from now\rThere should be no reason to believe \rI lived.\rDaybreak In this moment when the light starts up \rIn the east and rubs \rThe horizon until it catches fire,\rWe enter the fields to hoe,\rRow after row, among the small flags of onion, \rWaving off the dragonflies \rThat ladder the air.\rAnd tears the onions raise\rDo not begin in your eyes but in ours, \rIn the salt blown\rFrom one blister into another;\rThey begin in knowing\rYou will never waken to bear\rThe hour timed to a heart beat,\rThe wind pressing us closer to the ground.\rWhen the season ends,\rAnd the onions are unplugged from their sleep, \rWe won’t forget what you failed to see, \rAnd nothing will heal\rUnder the rain’s broken fingers.\n	'air':621 'almost':17 'alreadi':65,215 'among':608 'anoth':168,644 'ant':99,341 'appear':230 'armpit':147 'around':343 'autumn':331 'away':153 'bear':654 'beat':661 'becom':68 'beetl':120 'beg