618	Astrophil and Stella 2: Not at first sight, nor with a dribbèd shot	213		\nNot at first sight, nor with a dribbèd shot,    Love gave the wound which while I breathe will bleed:    But known worth did in mine of time proceed, Till by degrees it had full conquest got. I saw, and liked; I liked, but lovèd not;    I loved, but straight did not what love decreed:    At length to love’s decrees I, forced, agreed, Yet with repining at so partial lot.    Now even that footstep of lost liberty Is gone, and now like slave-born Muscovite I call it praise to suffer tyranny; And now employ the remnant of my wit    To make myself believe that all is well,    While with a feeling skill I paint my hell.\n	'2':4 'agre':76 'astrophil':1 'believ':118 'bleed':32 'born':98 'breath':30 'call':101 'conquest':48 'decre':67,73 'degre':44 'dribbèd':12,21 'employ':109 'even':85 'feel':126 'first':7,16 'footstep':87 'forc':75 'full':47 'gave':24 'gone':92 'got':49 'hell':131 'known':34 'length':69 'liberti':90 'like':53,55,95 'lost':89 'lot':83 'love':23,60,66,71 'lovèd':57 'make':116 'mine':38 'muscovit':99 'paint':129 'partial':82 'prais':103 'proceed':41 'remnant':111 'repin':79 'saw':51 'shot':13,22 'sight':8,17 'skill':127 'slave':97 'slave-born':96 'stella':3 'straight':62 'suffer':105 'till':42 'time':40 'tyranni':106 'well':122 'wit':114 'worth':35 'wound':26 'yet':77
619	Astrophil and Stella 5: It is most true, that eyes are formed to serve	213		\nIt is most true, that eyes are formed to serve The inward light; and that the heavenly part Ought to be king, from whose rules who do swerve, Rebels to Nature, strive for their own smart.     It is most true, what we call Cupid’s dart, An image is, which for ourselves we carve; And, fools, adore in temple of our heart, Till that good god make Church and churchman starve.     True, that true beauty virtue is indeed, Whereof this beauty can be but a shade, Which elements with mortal mixture breed; True, that on earth we are but pilgrims made,     And should in soul up to our country move; True; and yet true, that I must Stella love.\n	'5':4 'ador':71 'astrophil':1 'beauti':89,95 'breed':106 'call':57 'carv':68 'church':82 'churchman':84 'countri':123 'cupid':58 'dart':60 'earth':110 'element':102 'eye':10,20 'fool':70 'form':12,22 'god':80 'good':79 'heart':76 'heaven':31 'imag':62 'inde':92 'inward':26 'king':36 'light':27 'love':133 'made':115 'make':81 'mixtur':105 'mortal':104 'move':124 'must':131 'natur':45 'ought':33 'part':32 'pilgrim':114 'rebel':43 'rule':39 'serv':14,24 'shade':100 'smart':50 'soul':119 'starv':85 'stella':3,132 'strive':46 'swerv':42 'templ':73 'till':77 'true':8,18,54,86,88,107,125,128 'virtu':90 'whereof':93 'whose':38 'yet':127
620	Astrophil and Stella 101: Stella is sick, and in that sick-bed lies	213		\nStella is sick, and in that sick-bed lies Sweetness, that breathes and pants as oft as she; And grace, sick too, such fine conclusions tries That sickness brags itself best graced to be.     Beauty is sick, but sick in so fair guise That in that paleness beauty’s white we see; And joy, which is inseparate from these eyes, Stella now learns (strange case!) to weep in thee.    Love moves thy pain, and like a faithful page, As thy looks stir, runs up and down, to make All folks prest at thy will thy pain to assuage; Nature with care sweats for her darling’s sake,    Knowing worlds pass, ere she enough can find    Of such heaven stuff, to clothe so heavenly mind.\n	'101':4 'assuag':113 'astrophil':1 'beauti':50,63 'bed':13,23 'best':46 'brag':44 'breath':27 'care':116 'case':80 'cloth':136 'conclus':40 'darl':120 'enough':128 'ere':126 'eye':75 'fair':57 'faith':92 'find':130 'fine':39 'folk':105 'grace':35,47 'guis':58 'heaven':133,138 'insepar':72 'joy':69 'know':123 'learn':78 'lie':14,24 'like':90 'look':96 'love':85 'make':103 'mind':139 'move':86 'natur':114 'oft':31 'page':93 'pain':88,111 'pale':62 'pant':29 'pass':125 'prest':106 'run':98 'sake':122 'see':67 'sick':7,12,17,22,36,43,52,54 'sick-b':11,21 'stella':3,5,15,76 'stir':97 'strang':79 'stuff':134 'sweat':117 'sweet':25 'thee':84 'thi':87,95,108,110 'tri':41 'weep':82 'white':65 'world':124
621	Astrophil and Stella 102: Where be the roses gone, which sweetened so our eyes?	213		\nWhere be the roses gone, which sweetened so our eyes?     Where those red cheeks, which oft with fair increase did frame     The height of honor in the kindly badge of shame? Who hath the crimson weeds stolen from my morning skies? How doth the color vade of those vermilion dyes,     Which Nature's self did make, and self engrained the same!     I would know by what right this paleness overcame That hue, whose force my heart still unto thraldom ties?     Galen's adoptive sons, who by a beaten way     Their judgements hackney on, the fault on sickness lay; But feeling proof makes me say they mistake it far:     It is but love, which makes his paper perfect white     To write therein more fresh the story of delight, Whiles beauty's reddest ink Venus for him doth stir.\n	'102':4 'adopt':97 'astrophil':1 'badg':43 'beaten':102 'beauti':143 'cheek':28 'color':59 'crimson':49 'delight':141 'doth':57,150 'dye':64 'engrain':73 'eye':14,24 'fair':32 'far':122 'fault':109 'feel':114 'forc':88 'frame':35 'fresh':137 'galen':95 'gone':9,19 'hackney':106 'hath':47 'heart':90 'height':37 'honor':39 'hue':86 'increas':33 'ink':146 'judgement':105 'kind':42 'know':78 'lay':112 'love':126 'make':70,116,128 'mistak':120 'morn':54 'natur':66 'oft':30 'overcam':84 'pale':83 'paper':130 'perfect':131 'proof':115 'red':27 'reddest':145 'right':81 'rose':8,18 'say':118 'self':68,72 'shame':45 'sick':111 'sky':55 'son':98 'stella':3 'still':91 'stir':151 'stolen':51 'stori':139 'sweeten':11,21 'therein':135 'thraldom':93 'tie':94 'unto':92 'vade':60 'venus':147 'vermilion':63 'way':103 'weed':50 'while':142 'white':132 'whose':87 'would':77 'write':134
