672	The Geranium	285		\nIn the close covert of a grove\rBy nature formed for scenes of love,\rSaid Susan in a lucky hour:\r‘Observe yon sweet geranium flower.\rHow straight upon its stalk it stands,\rAnd tempts our violating hands,\rWhilst the soft bud, as yet unspread,\rHangs down its pale declining head.\rYet soon as it is ripe to blow,\rThe stems shall rise, the head shall glow.’\r‘Nature,’ said I, ‘my lovely Sue,\rTo all her followers lends a clue.\rHer simple laws themselves explain\rAs links of one continued chain;\rFor her the mysteries of creation\rAre but the works of generation.\rYon blushing, strong, triumphant flower\rIs in the crisis of its power:\rBut short, alas, its vigorous reign;\rHe sheds his seed, and drops again.\rThe bud that hangs in pale decay\rFeels not, as yet, the plastic ray.\rTomorrow’s sun shall bid him rise,\rThen, too, he sheds his seed, and dies.\rBut words, my love, are vain and weak; \rFor proof, let bright example speak.’\rThen straight before the wondering maid\rThe tree of life I gently laid.\r‘Observe, sweet Sue, his drooping head,\rHow pale, how languid, and how dead.\rYet let the sun of thy bright eyes\rShine but a moment, it shall rise.\rLet but the dew of thy soft hand\rRefresh the stem, it straight shall stand.\rAlready, see, it swells, it grows,\rIts head is redder than the rose,\rIts shriveled fruit, of dusky hue,\rNow glows—a present fit for Sue.\rThe balm of life each artery fills,\rAnd in o’erflowing drops distils.’\r‘Oh, me!’ cried Susan, ‘When is this?\rWhat strange tumultuous throbs of bliss!\rSure, never mortal till this hour\rFelt such emotion at a flower!\rOh, serpent, cunning to deceive,\rSure ’tis this tree that tempted Eve.\rThe crimson apples hang so fair\rAlas! what woman could forbear?’\r‘Well hast thou guessed, my love,’ I cried,\r‘It is the tree by which she died –\rThe tree which could alone content her.\rAll nature, Susan, seeks the centre.\rYet let us still poor Eve forgive,\rIt’s the tree by which we live.\rFor lovely women still it grows,\rAnd in the centre only blows.\rBut chief for thee it spreads its charms,\rFor paradise is in thy arms …’\rI ceased, for nature kindly here\rBegan to whisper in her ear,\rAnd lovely Sue lay softly panting\rWhile the geranium tree was planting,\r’Til in the heat of amorous strife\rShe burst the mellow tree of life.\r‘Oh, heaven!’ cried Susan with a sigh,\r‘The hour we taste – we surely die.\rStrange raptures seize my fainting frame,\rAnd all my body glows with flame.\rYet let me snatch one parting kiss\rTo tell my love I die with bliss –\rThat pleased thy Susan yields her breath;\rOh, who would live, if this be death?’\r\n	'ala':119,311 'alon':336 'alreadi':229 'amor':415 'appl':307 'arm':385 'arteri':260 'balm':256 'began':392 'bid':148 'bliss':280,465 'blow':60,371 'blush':106 'bodi':447 'breath':472 'bright':170,205 'bud':43,131 'burst':418 'ceas':387 'centr':344,369 'chain':92 'charm':379 'chief':373 'close':5 'clue':81 'content':337 'continu':91 'could':314,335 'covert':6 'creation':98 'cri':270,323,426 'crimson':306 'crisi':113 'cun':295 'dead':198 'death':480 'decay':136 'deceiv':297 'declin':51 'dew':217 'die':158,331,437,463 'distil':267 'droop':190 'drop':128,266 'duski':246 'ear':397 'emot':289 'erflow':265 'eve':304,350 'exampl':171 'explain':86 'eye':206 'faint':442 'fair':310 'feel':137 'felt':287 'fill':261 'fit':252 'flame':450 'flower':27,109,292 'follow':78 'forbear':315 'forgiv':351 'form':12 'frame':443 'fruit':244 'generat':104 'gentl':184 'geranium':2,26,406 'glow':68,249,448 'grove':9 'grow':234,365 'guess':319 'hand':39,221 'hang':47,133,308 'hast':317 'head':52,66,191,236 'heat':413 'heaven':425 'hour':22,286,432 'hue':247 'kind':390 'kiss':457 'laid':185 'languid':195 'law':84 'lay':401 'lend':79 'let':169,200,214,346,452 'life':182,258,423 'link':88 'live':359,476 'love':16,73,162,321,361,399,461 'lucki':21 'maid':178 'mellow':420 'moment':210 'mortal':283 'mysteri':96 'natur':11,69,340,389 'never':2