674	from The Rape of Lucrece	169		\nHer lily hand her rosy cheek lies under, \rCozening the pillow of a lawful kiss;\rWho, therefore angry, seems to part in sunder,\rSwelling on either side to want his bliss;\rBetween whose hills her head entombed is;\r   Where like a virtuous monument she lies,\r   To be admired of lewd unhallowed eyes.\rWithout the bed her other fair hand was,\rOn the green coverlet, whose perfect white\rShowed like an April daisy on the grass,\rWith pearly sweat resembling dew of night.\rHer eyes, like marigolds, had sheathed their light,\r   And canopied in darkness sweetly lay\r   Till they might open to adorn the day.\rHer hair like golden threads played with her breath\rO modest wantons, wanton modesty!\rShowing life’s triumph in the map of death,\rAnd death’s dim look in life’s mortality.\rEach in her sleep themselves so beautify\r   As if between them twain there were no strife,\r   But that life lived in death, and death in life.\rHer breasts like ivory globes circled with blue,\rA pair of maiden worlds unconquerèd,\rSave of their lord no bearing yoke they knew,\rAnd him by oath they truly honourèd.\rThese worlds in Tarquin new ambition bred,\r   Who like a foul usurper went about\r   From this fair throne to heave the owner out.\rWhat could he see but mightily he noted?\rWhat did he note but strongly he desired?\rWhat he beheld, on that he firmly doted,\rAnd in his will his willful eye he tired.\rWith more than admiration he admired\r   Her azure veins, her alabaster skin,\r   Her coral lips, her snow-white dimpled chin.\rAs the grim lion fawneth o’er his prey\rSharp hunger by the conquest satisfied,\rSo o’er this sleeping soul doth Tarquin stay,\rHis rage of lust by gazing qualified;\rSlacked, not suppressed; for, standing by her side,\r   His eye, which late this mutiny restrains,\r   Unto a greater uproar tempts his veins.\rAnd they, like straggling slaves for pillage fighting,\rObdurate vassals fell exploits effecting.\rIn bloody death and ravishment delighting,\rNor children’s tears nor mothers’ groans respecting,\rSwell in their pride, the onset still expecting.\r   Anon his beating heart, alarum striking,\r   Gives the hot charge and bids them do their liking.\rHis drumming heart cheers up his burning eye,\rHis eye commends the leading to his hand;\rHis hand, as proud of such a dignity,\rSmoking with pride, marched on to make his stand\rOn her bare breast, the heart of all her land,\r   Whose ranks of blue veins, as his hand did scale,\r   Left their round turrets destitute and pale.\rThey, mustering to the quiet cabinet\rWhere their dear governess and lady lies,\rDo tell her she is dreadfully beset\rAnd fright her with confusion of their cries.\rShe, much amazed, breaks ope her locked-up eyes,\r   Who, peeping forth this tumult to behold,\r   Are by his flaming torch dimmed and controlled.\rImagine her as one in dead of night\rFrom forth dull sleep by dreadful fancy waking,\rThat thinks she hath beheld some ghastly sprite,\rWhose grim aspect sets every joint a-shaking.\rWhat terror ‘tis! but she, in worser taking,\r   From sleep disturbèd, heedfully doth view\r   The sight which makes supposèd terror true.\rWrapped and confounded in a thousand fears,\rLike to a new-killed bird she trembling lies.\rShe dares not look; yet, winking, there appears\rQuick-shifting antics ugly in her eyes.\rSuch shadows are the weak brain’s forgeries,\r   Who, angry that the eyes fly from their lights,\r   In darkness daunts them with more dreadful sights.\rHis hand, that yet remains upon her breast\r(Rude ram, to batter such an ivory wall!)\rMay feel her heart (poor citizen) distressed,\rWounding itself to death, rise up and fall,\rBeating her bulk, that his hand shakes withal.\r   This moves in him more rage and lesser pity,\r   To make the breach and enter this sweet city. \r\n	'a-shak':522 'admir':53,257,259 'adorn':107 'alabast':264 'alarum':367 'amaz':469 'ambit':203 'angri':23,588 'anon':363 'antic':574 'a