689	Ode 487	291		\nWith last night’s wine still singing in my head, I sought the tavern at the break of day, Though half the world was still asleep in bed; The harp and flute were up and in full swing, And a most pleasant morning sound made they; Already was the wine-cup on the wing. ‘Reason,’ said I, ‘’t is past the time to start, If you would reach your daily destination, The holy city of intoxication.’   So did I pack him off, and he depart With a stout flask for fellow-traveller. Left to myself, the tavern-wench I spied, And sought to win her love by speaking fair; Alas! she turned upon me, scornful-eyed, And mocked my foolish hopes of winning her. Said she, her arching eyebrows like a bow: ‘Thou mark for all the shafts of evil tongues! Thou shalt not round my middle clasp me so, Like my good girdle – not for all thy songs! – So long as thou in all created things Seest but thyself the centre and the end. Go spread thy dainty nets for other wings – Too high the Anca’s nest for thee, my friend.’ Then took I shelter from that stormy sea In the good ark of wine; yet, woe is me! Saki and comrade and minstrel all by turns, She is of maidens the compendium Who my poor heart in such a fashion spurns. Self, HAFIZ, self! That thou must overcome! Hearken the wisdom of the tavern-daughter! Vain little baggage – well, upon my word! Thou fairy figment made of clay and water, As busy with thy beauty as a bird. Well, HAFIZ, Life’s a riddle – give it up: There is no answer to it but this cup.   \n	'487':2 'ala':115 'alreadi':49 'anca':193 'answer':291 'arch':134 'ark':211 'asleep':28 'baggag':258 'beauti':275 'bed':30 'bird':278 'bow':138 'break':19 'busi':272 'centr':178 'citi':77 'clasp':154 'clay':268 'compendium':231 'comrad':220 'creat':172 'cup':54,296 'daili':73 'dainti':185 'daughter':255 'day':21 'depart':88 'destin':74 'end':181 'evil':146 'eye':122 'eyebrow':135 'fair':114 'fairi':264 'fashion':239 'fellow':95 'fellow-travel':94 'figment':265 'flask':92 'flute':34 'fo