690	To a Young Lady, With Some Lampreys	248		\nWith lovers, ’twas of old the fashion\rBy presents to convey their passion;\rNo matter what the gift they sent,\rThe Lady saw that love was meant.\rFair Atalanta, as a favour,\rTook the boar’s head her Hero gave her;\rNor could the bristly thing affront her,\r’Twas a fit present from a hunter.\rWhen Squires send woodcocks to the dame,\rIt serves to show their absent flame:\rSome by a snip of woven hair,\rIn posied lockets bribe the fair;\rHow many mercenary matches\rHave sprung from Di’mond-rings and watches!\rBut hold – a ring, a watch, a locket,\rWould drain at once a Poet’s pocket;\rHe should send songs that cost him nought,\rNor ev’n he prodigal of thought.\r   Why then send Lampreys? fye, for shame!\r’Twill set a virgin’s blood on flame.\rThis to fifteen a proper gift!\rIt might lend sixty five a lift. \r   I know your maiden Aunt will scold,\rAnd think my present somewhat bold.\rI see her lift her hands and eyes.\r   ‘What eat it, Niece? eat Spanish flies!\r‘Lamprey’s a most immodest diet:\r‘You’ll neither wake nor sleep in quiet.\r‘Should I to night eat Sago cream,\r‘’Twould make me blush to tell my dream;\r‘If I eat Lobster, ’tis so warming,\r‘That ev’ry man I see looks charming;\r‘Wherefore had not the filthy fellow\r‘Laid Rochester upon your pillow?\r‘I vow and swear, I think the present\r‘Had been as modest and as decent.\r   ‘Who has her virtue in her power?\r‘Each day has its unguarded hour;\r‘Always in danger of undoing,\r‘A prawn, a shrimp may prove our ruin!\r   ‘The shepherdess, who lives on salad,\r‘To cool her youth, controuls her palate;\r‘Should Dian’s maids turn liqu’rish livers,\r‘And of huge lampreys rob the rivers,\r‘Then all beside each glade and Visto,\r‘You’d see Nymphs lying like Calisto.\r   ‘The man who meant to heat your blood,\r‘Needs not himself such vicious food –’\r   In this, I own, your Aunt is clear,\rI sent you what I well might spare:\rFor when I see you, (without joking)\rYour eyes, lips, breasts, are so provoking,\rThey set my heart more cock-a-hoop,\rThan could whole seas of craw-fish soupe.\r\n	'absent':75 'affront':54 'alway':273 'atalanta':36 'aunt':166,347 'besid':316 'blood':146,335 'blush':214 'boar':42 'bold':174 'breast':368 'bribe':87 'brist':52 'calisto':327 'charm':233 'clear':349 'cock':378 'cock-a-hoop':377 'controul':296 'convey':18 'cool':293 'cost':124 'could':50,382 'craw':387 'craw-fish':386 'cream':210 'd':322 'dame':69 'danger':275 'day':268 'decent':259 'di':97 'dian':300 'diet':195 'drain':112 'dream':218 'eat':184,187,208,221 'ev':128,227 'eye':182,366 'fair':35,89 'fashion':14 'favour':39 'fellow':239 'fifteen':151 'filthi':238 'fish':388 'fit':58 'five':159 'flame':76,148 'fli':189 'food':341 'fye':138 'gave':47 'gift':25,154 'glade':318 'hair':83 'hand':180 'head':44 'heart':375 'heat':333 'hero':46 'hold':104 'hoop':380 'hour':272 'huge':309 'hunter':62 'immodest':194 'joke':364 'know':163 'ladi':4,29 'laid':240 'lamprey':7,137,190,310 'lend':157 'lie':325 'lift':161,178 'like':326 'lip':367 'liqu':304 'live':289 'liver':306 'll':197 'lobster':222 'locket':86,110 'look':232 'love':32 'lover':9 'maid':302 'maiden':165 'make':212 'man':229,329 'mani':91 'match':93 'matter':22 'may':282 'meant':34,331 'mercenari':92 'might':156,356 'modest':256 'mond':99 'mond-r':98 'n':129 'need':336 'neither':198 'niec':186 'night':207 'nought':126 'nymph':324 'old':12 'palat':298 'passion':20 'pillow':244 'pocket':118 'poet':116 'posi':85 'power':266 'prawn':279 'present':16,59,172,252 'prodig':131 'proper':153 'prove':283 'provok':371 'quiet':203 'ring':100,106 'rish':305 'river':313 'rob':311 'rochest':241 'ruin':285 'ry':228 'sago':209 'salad':291 'saw':30 'scold':168 'sea':384 'see':176,231,323,361 'send':65,121,136 'sent':27,351 'serv':71 'set':142,373 'shame':140 'shepherdess':287 'show':73 'shrimp':281 'sixti':158 'sleep':201 'snip':80 'somewhat':173 'song':122 'soup':389 'spanish':188 'spare':357 'sprung':95 'squir':64 