736	The Weakness	20		\nThat time my grandmother dragged me through the perfume aisles at Saks, she held me up  by my arm, hissing, “Stand up,” through clenched teeth, her eyes bright as a dog’s cornered in the light. She said it over and over, as if she were Jesus, and I were dead. She had been solid as a tree, a fur around her neck, a light-skinned matron whose car was parked, who walked on swirling marble and passed through brass openings—in 1945. There was not even a black elevator operator at Saks. The saleswoman had brought velvet  leggings to lace me in, and cooed, as if in the service of all grandmothers.  My grandmother had smiled, but not  hungrily, not like my mother who hated them, but wanted to please,  and they had smiled back, as if they were wearing wooden collars.  When my legs gave out, my grandmother  dragged me up and held me like God  holds saints by the roots of the hair. I begged her to believe I couldn’t help it. Stumbling,  her face white with sweat, she pushed me through the crowd, rushing away from those eyes  that saw through  her clothes, under her skin, all the way down  to the transparent  genes confessing.\n	'1945':86 'aisl':12 'arm':21 'around':63 'away':193 'back':139 'beg':171 'believ':174 'black':92 'brass':83 'bright':30 'brought':100 'car':72 'clench':26 'cloth':201 'collar':146 'confess':213 'coo':108 'corner':35 'couldn':176 'crowd':191 'dead':53 'dog':33 'drag':7,154 'elev':93 'even':90 'eye':29,196 'face':182 'fur':62 'gave':150 'gene':212 'god':161 'grandmoth':6,116,118,153 'hair':169 'hate':129 'held':16,158 'help':178 'hiss':22 'hold':162 'hungrili':123 'jesus':49 'lace':104 'leg':102,149 'light':38,68 'light-skin':67 'like':125,160 'marbl':79 'matron':70 'mother':127 'neck':65 'open':84 'oper':94 'park':74 'pass':81 'perfum':11 'pleas':134 'push':187 'root':166 'rush':192 'said':40 'saint':163 'sak':14,96 'saleswoman':98 'saw':198 'servic':113 'skin':69,204 'smile':120,138 'solid':57 'stand':23 'stumbl':180 'sweat':185 's