833	The Metaphysical Amorist	310		\nYou are the problem I propose, My dear, the text my musings glose: I call you for convenience love. By definition you’re a cause Inferred by necessary laws— You are so to the saints above. But in this shadowy lower life I sleep with a terrestrial wife And earthy children I beget. Love is a fiction I must use, A privilege I can abuse, And sometimes something I forget. Now, in the heavenly other place Love is in the eternal mind The luminous form whose shade she is, A ghost discarnate, thought defined. She was so to my early bliss, She is so while I comprehend The forms my senses apprehend, And in the end she will be so. Her whom my hands embrace I kiss, Her whom my mind infers I know. The one exists in time and space And as she was she will not be; The other is in her own grace And is She is eternally. Plato! you shall not plague my life. I married a terrestrial wife. And Hume! she is not mere sensation In sequence of observed relation. She has two forms—ah, thank you, Duns!—, I know her in both ways at once. I knew her, yes, before I knew her, And by both means I must construe her, And none among you shall undo her.\n	'abus':68 'ah':193 'among':223 'amorist':3 'apprehend':115 'beget':56 'bliss':104 'call':18 'caus':28 'children':54 'comprehend':110 'constru':219 'conveni':21 'dear':11 'defin':97 'definit':24 'discarn':95 'dun':196 'earli':103 'earthi':53 'embrac':128 'end':119 'etern':84,164 'exist':140 'fiction':60 'forget':73 'form':88,112,192 'ghost':94 'glose':16 'grace':159 'hand':127 'heaven':77 'hume':178 'infer':29,135 'kiss':130 'knew':206,211 'know':137,198 'law':32 'life':45,171 'love':22,57,80 'lower':44 'lumin':87 'marri':173 'mean':216 'mere':182 'metaphys':2 'mind':85,134 'muse':15 'must':62,218 'necessari':31 'none':222 'observ':187 'one':139 'place':79 'plagu':169 'plato':165 'privileg':65 'problem':7 'propos':9 're':26 'relat':188 'saint':38 'sens':114 'sensat':183 'sequenc':185 'shade':90 'shadowi':43 'shall':16