835	from Epigrams:  A Journal, #8	310		\nIf wisdom, as it seems it is,\rBe the recovery of some bliss\rFrom the conditions of disaster—\rTerror the servant, man the master—\rIt does not follow we should seek \rCrises to prove ourselves unweak. \rMuch of our lives, God knows, is error, \rBut who will trifle with unrest? \rThese fools who would solicit terror, \rObsessed with being unobsessed; \rProfessionals of experience\rWho have disasters to withstand them \rAs if fear never had unmanned them, \rFlaunt a presumptuous innocence.\rI have preferred indifference.\n	'8':5 'bliss':18 'condit':21 'crise':37 'disast':23,71 'epigram':2 'error':49 'experi':68 'fear':77 'flaunt':82 'follow':33 'fool':57 'god':46 'indiffer':89 'innoc':85 'journal':4 'know':47 'live':45 'man':27 'master':29 'much':42 'never':78 'obsess':62 'prefer':88 'presumptu':84 'profession':66 'prove':39 'recoveri':15 'seek':36 'seem':10 'servant':26 'solicit':60 'terror':24,61 'trifl':53 'unman':80 'unobsess':65 'unrest':55 'unweak':41 'wisdom':7 'withstand':73 'would':59
