872	Second Thoughts	315		\n. . . and then of course the weeping: some demurely, some \rflamboyantly. Those elegiac tears, if shed\renough, will alter a face and the person\rbehind the face. We all know that erosion\ris a mighty thing, and even—for example—\rthe seemingly permanent, hard-black Mississippi banks \rundo and slip south. In a sense, the delta\rat New Orleans—the land gone silt, and rebuilt—\ris the Mississippi’s second thought. “My pet, \ryour wiles have altered my earlier obstinacy,\rand the vision of you in your luxury stateroom beckons;\rI shall join you for your voyage on the Gigantic\r—what? oh. Titanic”—is a tragic second thought.\rA happy one: when Skyler and I decided to try again \rto “save the marriage.” Now we’re lazing in a pour \rof Sunday morning light as orangely voluptuous\ras marmalade. A simile’s a first thought,\rthen an equaled next. She slips back into sleep,\rand now I’m reading about the night that shady London dandy \rCharles Augustus Howell (1869) unshoveled the grave\rat Highgate, broke the coffin, and looted her bone breast\rof “the book in question, bound in rough gray calf, and with \rred edges to the leaves,” on eager orders from Rossetti \r—who’d had second thoughts in seven years, desiring\rto publish now a volume of his verses (1870, Poems). \rLizzie’s death-stenched pages were saturated\rwith disinfectant by a medical practitioner “who\ris drying them leaf by leaf”—and then they joined the world\rof woven radish baskets, bobbered fishing skeins, and god dolls \rin their second life as art on a museum wall; a world where \rthe “conversion pool” saw swimmers step in white robes\rfrom its farther end, reborn to new religion; and the lumbering\rland animals said no, and gave up legs, and so their legs rolled up \rlike stored-away and useless rugs inside them, and they returned \rto the waters, and birthed and breached in the waters,\rand made the waters their orchestral glory,\rand spouted out their great Ionic columns of air and water \rin the touch of the changing mind of Earth,\rthat’s sunlit at times\rand at other times darkened.\r\n	'1869':172 '1870':225 'air':348 'alter':20,79 'anim':298 'art':269 'augustus':170 'away':314 'back':154 'bank':49 'basket':257 'beckon':92 'behind':26 'birth':327 'black':47 'bobber':258 'bone':184 'book':188 'bound':191 'breach':329 'breast':185 'broke':178 'calf':195 'chang':356 'charl':169 'coffin':180 'column':346 'convers':278 'cours':6 'd':209 'dandi':168 'darken':369 'death':230 'death-stench':229 'decid':118 'delta':58 'demur':10 'desir':216 'disinfect':236 'doll':263 'dri':243 'eager':204 'earlier':81 'earth':359 'edg':199 'elegiac':14 'end':289 'enough':18 'equal':150 'eros':33 'even':39 'exampl':41 'face':22,28 'farther':288 'first':146 'fish':259 'flamboy':12 'gave':302 'gigant':102 'glori':339 'god':262 'gone':64 'grave':175 'gray':194 'great':344 'happi':112 'hard':46 'hard-black':45 'highgat':177 'howel':171 'insid':318 'ionic':345 'join':95,251 'know':31 'land':63,297 'laze':129 'leaf':245,247 'leav':202 'leg':304,308 'life':267 'light':136 'like':311 'lizzi':227 'london':167 'loot':182 'lumber':296 'luxuri':90 'm':160 'made':334 'marmalad':141 'marriag':125 'medic':239 'mighti':36 'mind':357 'mississippi':48,70 'morn':135 'museum':272 'new':60,292 'next':151 'night':164 'obstinaci':82 'oh':104 'one':113 'orang':138 'orchestr':338 'order':205 'orlean':61 'page':232 'perman':44 'person':25 'pet':75 'poem':226 'pool':279 'pour':132 'practition':240 'publish':218 'question':190 'radish':256 're':128 'read':161 'reborn':290 'rebuilt':67 'red':198 'religion':293 'return':322 'robe':285 'roll':309 'rossetti':207 'rough':193 'rug':317 'said':299 'satur':234 'save':123 'saw':280 'second':1,72,109,211,266 'seem':43 'sens':56 'seven':214 'shadi':166 'shall':94 'shed':17 'silt':65 'simil':143 'skein':260 'skyler':115 'sleep':156 'slip':52,153 'south':53 'spout':341 'stateroom':91 'stench':231 'step':282 'store':313 'stored-away':312 'sunday':134 '