863	The Fly	314		\nO hideous little bat, the size of snot, \rWith polyhedral eye and shabby clothes, \rTo populate the stinking cat you walk \rThe promontory of the dead man’s nose, \rClimb with the fine leg of a Duncan-Phyfe\r  The smoking mountains of my food \r    And in a comic mood \r  In mid-air take to bed a wife.\rRiding and riding with your filth of hair \rOn gluey foot or wing, forever coy,\rHot from the compost and green sweet decay, \rSounding your buzzer like an urchin toy\rYou dot all whiteness with diminutive stool,\r  In the tight belly of the dead\r    Burrow with hungry head\r  And inlay maggots like a jewel.\rAt your approach the great horse stomps and paws \rBringing the hurricane of his heavy tail;\rShod in disease you dare to kiss my hand\rWhich sweeps against you like an angry flail; \rStill you return, return, trusting your wing \r  To draw you from the hunter’s reach\r    That learns to kill to teach\r  Disorder to the tinier thing.\rMy peace is your disaster. For your death \rChildren like spiders cup their pretty hands \rAnd wives resort to chemistry of war.\rIn fens of sticky paper and quicksands\rYou glue yourself to death. Where you are stuck \r  You struggle hideously and beg,\r    You amputate your leg\r  Imbedded in the amber muck.\rBut I, a man, must swat you with my hate, \rSlap you across the air and crush your flight, \rMust mangle with my shoe and smear your blood, \rExpose your little guts pasty and white,\rKnock your head sidewise like a drunkard’s hat, \r  Pin your wings under like a crow’s,\r    Tear off your flimsy clothes\r  And beat you as one beats a rat.\rThen like Gargantua I stride among\rThe corpses strewn like raisins in the dust, \rThe broken bodies of the narrow dead\rThat catch the throat with fingers of disgust. \rI sweep. One gyrates like a top and falls\r  And stunned, stone blind, and deaf\r    Buzzes its frightful F\r  And dies between three cannibals.\n	'across':239 'air':56,241 'amber':225 'among':297 'am