865	Troop Train	314		\nIt stops the town we come through. Workers raise \rTheir oily arms in good salute and grin. \rKids scream as at a circus. Business men \rGlance hopefully and go their measured way. \rAnd women standing at their dumbstruck door \rMore slowly wave and seem to warn us back, \rAs if a tear blinding the course of war\rMight once dissolve our iron in their sweet wish.\rFruit of the world, O clustered on ourselves \rWe hang as from a cornucopia\rIn total friendliness, with faces bunched\rTo spray the streets with catcalls and with leers. \rA bottle smashes on the moving ties\rAnd eyes fixed on a lady smiling pink\rStretch like a rubber-band and snap and sting \rThe mouth that wants the drink-of-water kiss.\rAnd on through crummy continents and days, \rDeliberate, grimy, slightly drunk we crawl,\rThe good-bad boys of circumstance and chance, \rWhose bucket-helmets bang the empty wall \rWhere twist the murdered bodies of our packs \rNext to the guns that only seem themselves. \rAnd distance like a strap adjusted shrinks, \rTightens across the shoulder and holds firm.\rHere is a deck of cards; out of this hand \rDealer, deal me my luck, a pair of bulls,\rThe right draw to a flush, the one-eyed jack. \rDiamonds and hearts are red but spades are black, \rAnd spades are spades and clubs are cloversblack. \rBut deal me winners, souvenirs of peace. \rThis stands to reason and arithmetic, \rLuck also travels and not all come back.\rTrains lead to ships and ships to death or trains, \rAnd trains to death or trucks, and trucks to death, \rOr trucks lead to the march, the march to death, \rOr that survival which is all our hope;\rAnd death leads back to trucks and trains and ships, \rBut life leads to the march, O flag! at last \rThe place of life found after trains and death\rNightfall of nations brilliant after war.\n	'across':187 'adjust':184 'also':255 'arithmet':253 'arm':14 'back':50,261,303 'bad':149 'band':118 'bang':159 'black':231,240 'blind':55 'bod