868	The Conscientious Objector	314		\nThe gates clanged and they walked you into jail \rMore tense than felons but relieved to find\rThe hostile world shut out, the flags that dripped \rFrom every mother’s windowpane, obscene \rThe bloodlust sweating from the public heart, \rThe dog authority slavering at your throat. \rA sense of quiet, of pulling down the blind \rPossessed you. Punishment you felt was clean.\rThe decks, the catwalks, and the narrow light \rComposed a ship. This was a mutinous crew \rTroubling the captains for plain decencies, \rA Mayflower brim with pilgrims headed out \rTo establish new theocracies to west,\rA Noah’s ark coasting the topmost seas \rTen miles above the sodomites and fish. \rThese inmates loved the only living doves.\rLike all men hunted from the world you made \rA good community, voyaging the storm \rTo no safe Plymouth or green Ararat;\rTrouble or calm, the men with Bibles prayed, \rThe gaunt politicals construed our hate. \rThe opposite of all armies, you were best \rOpposing uniformity and yourselves;\rPrison and personality were your fate.\rYou suffered not so physically but knew \rMaltreatment, hunger, ennui of the mind. \rWell might the soldier kissing the hot beach \rErupting in his face damn all your kind. \rYet you who saved neither yourselves nor us \rAre equally with those who shed the blood \rThe heroes of our cause. Your conscience is \rWhat we come back to in the armistice.\n	'ararat':144 'ark':104 'armi':163 'armistic':237 'author':45 'back':233 'beach':197 'best':166 'bibl':151 'blind':58 'blood':221 'bloodlust':37 'brim':90 'calm':147 'captain':84 'catwalk':69 'caus':226 'clang':6 'clean':65 'coast':105 'come':232 'communiti':134 'compos':74 'conscienc':228 'conscienti':2 'constru':156 'crew':81 'damn':202 'decenc':87 'deck':67 'dog':44 'dove':122 'drip':29 'ennui':186 'equal':215 'erupt':198 'establish':96 'everi':31 'face':201 'fate':176 'felon':16 'felt':63 'find':20 'fish':115 'flag':27 'gate':5 'gaunt':154 'g