903	Song	317		\nObserve the cautious toadstools      still on the lawn today though they grow over-evening;      sun shrinks them away. Pale and proper and rootless,      they righteously extort their living from the living.     I have been their sort. See by our blocked foundation      the cold, archaic clay, stiff and clinging and sterile      as children mold at play or as the Lord God fashioned      before He breathed it breath. The earth we dig and carry     for flowers, is strong in death. Woman, we are the rich     soil, friable and humble,  where all our murders rot,     where our old deaths crumble  and fortify my reach     far from you, wide and free,  though I have set my root      in you and am your tree.\n	'archaic':46 'away':20 'block':42 'breath':66,68 'carri':74 'cautious':4 'children':54 'clay':47 'cling':50 'cold':45 'crumbl':99 'death':80,98 'dig':72 'earth':70 'even':16 'extort':28 'far':104 'fashion':63 'flower':76 'fortifi':101 'foundat':43 'free':109 'friabl':87 'god':62 'grow':13 'humbl':89 'lawn':9 'live':30,33 'lord':61 'mold':55 'murder':93 'observ':2 'old':97 'over-even':14 'pale':21 'play':57 'proper':23 'reach':103 'rich':85 'righteous':27 'root':115 'rootless':25 'rot':94 'see':39 'set':113 'shrink':18 'soil':86 'song':1 'sort':38 'steril':52 'stiff':48 'still':6 'strong':78 'sun':17 'though':11,110 'toadstool':5 'today':10 'tree':121 'wide':107 'woman':81
