908	Lyell’s Hypothesis Again	318		\nThe mountain road ends here,   Broken away in the chasm where   The bridge washed out years ago.   The first scarlet larkspur glitters   In the first patch of April Morning sunlight. The engorged creek   Roars and rustles like a military   Ball. Here by the waterfall,   Insuperable life, flushed With the equinox, sentient   And sentimental, falls away To the sea and death. The tissue   Of sympathy and agony That binds the flesh in its Nessus' shirt;   The clotted cobweb of unself   And self; sheds itself and flecks   The sun's bed with darts of blossom   Like flagellant blood above   The water bursting in the vibrant   Air. This ego, bound by personal   Tragedy and the vast Impersonal vindictiveness Of the ruined and ruining world,   Pauses in this immortality, As passionate, as apathetic, As the lava flow that burned here once;   And stopped here; and said, 'This far   And no further.' And spoke thereafter   In the simple diction of stone. Naked in the warm April air,   We lie under the redwoods,   In the sunny lee of a cliff.   As you kneel above me I see   Tiny red marks on your flanks Like bites, where the redwood cones   Have pressed into your flesh.   You can find just the same marks   In the lignite in the cliff Over our heads. Sequoia Langsdorfii	'ago':21 'agoni':70 'air':108,166 'apathet':133 'april':32,165 'away':11,59 'ball':44 'bed':93 'bind':72 'bite':193 'blood':100 'blossom':97 'bound':111 'bridg':17 'broken':10 'burn':139 'burst':104 'chasm':14 'cliff':178,215 'clot':80 'cobweb':81 'cone':197 'creek':37 'dart':95 'death':64 'diction':158 'ego':110 'end':8 'engorg':36 'equinox':54 'fall':58 'far':148 'find':205 'first':23,29 'flagel':99 'flank':191 'fleck':89 'flesh':74,202 'flow':137 'flush':51 'glitter':26 'head':218 'hypothesi':3 'immort':129 'imperson':118 'insuper':49 'kneel':181 'langsdorfii':220 'larkspur':25 'lava':136 'lee':175 'lie':168 'life':50 'lignit':212 'like':41,98,192 'lyell':1 'mark':188,209 'mili