933	Jet	322		\nSometimes I wish I were still out on the back porch, drinking jet fuel   with the boys, getting louder and louder   as the empty cans drop out of our paws   like booster rockets falling back to Earth and we soar up into the summer stars.   Summer. The big sky river rushes overhead,   bearing asteroids and mist, blind fish   and old space suits with skeletons inside.   On Earth, men celebrate their hairiness, and it is good, a way of letting life out of the box, uncapping the bottle to let the effervescence gush through the narrow, usually constricted neck. And now the crickets plug in their appliances   in unison, and then the fireflies flash dots and dashes in the grass, like punctuation   for the labyrinthine, untrue tales of sex   someone is telling in the dark, though no one really hears. We gaze into the night as if remembering the bright unbroken planet   we once came from, to which we will never   be permitted to return. We are amazed how hurt we are. We would give anything for what we have.\n	'amaz':168 'anyth':176 'applianc':107 'asteroid':55 'back':11,36 'bear':54 'big':49 'blind':58 'booster':33 'bottl':88 'box':85 'boy':18 'bright':150 'came':155 'can':26 'celebr':70 'constrict':98 'cricket':103 'dark':135 'dash':117 'dot':115 'drink':13 'drop':27 'earth':38,68 'effervesc':92 'empti':25 'fall':35 'firefli':113 'fish':59 'flash':114 'fuel':15 'gaze':142 'get':19 'give':175 'good':76 'grass':120 'gush':93 'hairi':72 'hear':140 'hurt':170 'insid':66 'jet':1,14 'labyrinthin':125 'let':80,90 'life':81 'like':32,121 'louder':20,22 'men':69 'mist':57 'narrow':96 'neck':99 'never':161 'night':145 'old':61 'one':138 'overhead':53 'paw':31 'permit':163 'planet':152 'plug':104 'porch':12 'punctuat':122 'realli':139 'rememb':148 'return':165 'river':51 'rocket':34 'rush':52 'sex':129 'skeleton':65 'sky':50 'soar':41 'someon':130 'sometim':2 'space':62 'star':46 'still':7 'suit':63 'summer':45,47 'tale':127 'tell':132 'though':136 'unbroken':151 'uncap