964	The Curtain	321		\nJust over the horizon a great machine of death is roaring and rearing. \rWe can hear it always. Earthquake, starvation, the ever-renewing sump of corpse-flesh.\rBut in this valley the snow falls silently all day, and out our window \rWe see the curtain of it shifting and folding, hiding us away in our little house,\rWe see earth smoothened and beautified, made like a fantasy, the snow-clad trees\rSo graceful. In our new bed, which is big enough to seem like the north pasture almost\rWith our two cats, Cooker and Smudgins, lying undisturbed in the southeastern and southwestern corners,\rWe lie loving and warm, looking out from time to time. “Snowbound,” we say. We speak of the poet\rWho lived with his young housekeeper long ago in the mountains of the western province, the kingdom\rOf cruelty, where heads fell like wilted flowers and snow fell for many months\rAcross the pass and drifted deep in the vale. In our kitchen the maple-fire murmurs\rIn our stove. We eat cheese and new-made bread and jumbo Spanish olives\rWhich have been steeped in our special brine of jalapeños and garlic and dill and thyme.\rWe have a nip or two from the small inexpensive cognac that makes us smile and sigh.\rFor a while we close the immense index of images that is our lives—for instance,\rThe child on the Mescalero reservation in New Mexico sitting naked in 1966 outside his family’s hut,\rCovered with sores, unable to speak. But of course we see the child every day,\rWe hold out our hands, we touch him shyly, we make offerings to his implacability.\rNo, the index cannot close. And how shall we survive? We don’t and cannot and will never\rKnow. Beyond the horizon a great unceasing noise is undeniable. The machine,\rLike an immense clanking vibrating shuddering unnameable contraption as big as a house, as big as the whole town,\rMay break through and lurch into our valley at any moment, at any moment.\rCheers, baby. Here’s to us. See how the curtain of snow wavers and then falls back.\n	'1966':252 'across':159 'ago':135 'almost':93 'alway':20 'away':57 'babi':352 'back':367 'beautifi':67 'bed':82 'beyond':307 'big':85,327,332 'bread':186 'break':338 'brine':198 'cannot':291,302 'cat':97 'cheer':351 'chees':181 'child':241,270 'clad':75 'clank':321 'close':228,292 'cognac':217 'contrapt':325 'cooker':98 'corner':108 'corps':30 'corpse-flesh':29 'cours':266 'cover':258 'cruelti':146 'curtain':2,49,360 'day':41,272 'death':11 'deep':164 'dill':204 'drift':163 'earth':64 'earthquak':21 'eat':180 'enough':86 'ever':25 'ever-renew':24 'everi':271 'fall':38,366 'famili':255 'fantasi':71 'fell':149,155 'fire':174 'flesh':31 'flower':152 'fold':54 'garlic':202 'grace':78 'great':8,311 'hand':277 'head':148 'hear':18 'hide':55 'hold':274 'horizon':6,309 'hous':61,330 'housekeep':133 'hut':257 'imag':233 'immens':230,320 'implac':287 'index':231,290 'inexpens':216 'instanc':239 'jalapeño':200 'jumbo':188 'kingdom':144 'kitchen':170 'know':306 'lie':101,110 'like':69,89,150,318 'littl':60 'live':129,237 'long':134 'look':114 'love':111 'lurch':341 'machin':9,317 'made':68,185 'make':219,283 'mani':157 'mapl':173 'maple-fir':172 'may':337 'mescalero':244 'mexico':248 'moment':347,350 'month':158 'mountain':138 'murmur':175 'nake':250 'never':305 'new':81,184,247 'new-mad':183 'nip':210 'nois':313 'north':91 'offer':284 'oliv':190 'outsid':253 'pass':161 'pastur':92 'poet':127 'provinc':142 'rear':15 'renew':26 'reserv':245 'roar':13 'say':122 'see':47,63,268,357 'seem':88 'shall':295 'shift':52 'shudder':323 'shyli':281 'sigh':223 'silent':39 'sit':249 'small':215 'smile':221 'smoothen':65 'smudgin':100 'snow':37,74,154,362 'snow-clad':73 'snowbound':120 'sore':260 'southeastern':105 'southwestern':107 'spanish':189 'speak':124,263 'special':197 'starvat':22 'steep':194 'stove':178 'sump':27 'surviv':297 'thyme':206 'time':117,119 'touch':279 'town':336 'tree':76 'two':96,212 'unabl':261 'unceas':312 'undeni':315 'undisturb':102 'unnam':324