970	Boil	127		\nBoil over—it’s what the nerves do,   Watch them seethe when stimulated, Murmurs the man at the stove   To the one at the fridge— Watch that electric impulse that finally makes them   Fume and fizz at either Frayed end. If you could grasp a bundle Of nerves in your fist like a jumper cable, and sense that Python’s writhe, or a garden hose when the pressure’s   High and it wilfully weaves about Trying its best to get away from you— You’d see how nothing is passive, We’re all—I mean from our elephant sun, ejaculant   Great-grandfather, cascading down To weightless   Unstoppable neutrinos Leaving their silvery trace   In vacuum chambers, in Effervescent lines, twisted   Madly in our madhouse jackets, Rules, laws, which we are seething to break   Though to rupture them might be of course to die, Or, possibly,   To change: Boil, it’s what water And everything else teaches.\n	'away':82 'best':79 'boil':1,2,149 'break':134 'bundl':47 'cabl':56 'cascad':105 'chamber':117 'chang':148 'could':44 'cours':142 'd':86 'die':144 'effervesc':119 'either':39 'ejacul':101 'electr':29 'eleph':99 'els':156 'end':41 'everyth':155 'final':32 'fist':52 'fizz':37 'fray':40 'fridg':26 'fume':35 'garden':65 'get':81 'grandfath':104 'grasp':45 'great':103 'great-grandfath':102 'high':71 'hose':66 'impuls':30 'jacket':126 'jumper':55 'law':128 'leav':111 'like':53 'line':120 'mad':122 'madhous':125 'make':33 'man':17 'mean':96 'might':139 'murmur':15 'nerv':8,49 'neutrino':110 'noth':89 'one':23 'passiv':91 'possibl':146 'pressur':69 'python':60 're':93 'rule':127 'ruptur':137 'see':87 'seeth':12,132 'sens':58 'silveri':113 'stimul':14 'stove':20 'sun':100 'teach':157 'though':135 'trace':114 'tri':77 'twist':121 'unstopp':109 'vacuum':116 'watch':10,27 'water':153 'weav':75 'weightless':108 'wil':74 'writh':62
971	Nude Descending	127		\nLike a bowerbird trailing a beakful of weeds   Like prize ribbons for the very best The lover, producer   Of another’s pleasure He whom her swollen lips await Might wing through any day of the decade A form of health insurance   For which it is never too late Titanic, silver brush Hindenburg, of exploding cigars a climax The watery below, the fiery above Ashes of print between—pigment between If the crippled woman were to descend   From her bed, her fortress beyond midnight Downstairs (nude/staircase) to the kitchen   Naked to sit at the table (writing/thinking) She might hear the washer spin like a full orchestra   Complete a cycle like a train crash Before the fiend would stare through the window   Step smoothly into the kitchen, stop some clocks. Envy shapes a fig tree in one’s breast,   That is, bluntly to say, a cancer, That is to say In a mind, a fertile windy field. A murdered child. Well then, fear, primarily of falling.   Ebony surf toils on the beach, a glaze At the same moment I am (from a cliff) falling   The kitchen fiend removes his Dior tie Places his hand over the woman’s   And softly says: I am the lover. Now if the crippled woman began to dance   To pirouette, to rumba Growling for her child Her burning page, the devil would be shamed (Materialism is not for everyone / Religion is   The extension of politics by other means	'anoth':22 'ash':66 'await':30 'beach':172 'beak':8 'bed':81 'began':211 'best':17 'beyond':84 'blunt':142 'bowerbird':5 'breast':139 'brush':53 'burn':223 'cancer':146 'child':160,221 'cigar':57 'cliff':183 'climax':59 'clock':130 'complet':108 'crash':114 'crippl':74,209 'cycl':110 'danc':213 'day':35 'decad':38 'descend':2,78 'devil':226 'dior':190 'downstair':86 'eboni':167 'envi':131 'everyon':234 'explod':56 'extens':238 'fall':166,184 'fear':163 'fertil':155 'field':157 'fiend':117,187 'fieri':64 'fig':134 'form':40 'fortress':83 'full':106 'glaze':174 'growl':218 'hand':194 'health':42 'hear':10