981	Fall River	327		\nWhen I wake now it’s below ocherous, saw-ridged \rpine beams. Haze streaks all three windows. I look up \rat the dog-eared, glossy magazine photo\rI’ve taken with me for years. It gets tacked\rlike a claim to some new wall in the next place—\rBill Russell & Wilt Chamberlain, one on one\rthe final game of the 1969 NBA championship,\rtwo hard men snapped elbowing & snatching at a basketball \ras if it were a moment one of them might stay inside \rforever. I was with\rmy father the night that game played\ron a fuzzy color television, in a jammed Fall River bar. \rSeagram & beer chasers for hoarse ex-jocks,\rsmoke rifting the air. A drunk called him “Tiger”\rand asked about the year he’d made all-state guard—\rpoint man, ball-hawk, pacer. Something he rarely spoke \rof, & almost always with a gruff mix of impatience \rand shyness. Each year,\rdays painting suburban tract houses & fighting \rwith contractors followed by\rnight shifts at the fire station\rfollowed by his kids swarming at breakfast\rand my mother trying to stay out of his way,\reach of the many stone-hard moments between 1941 & 1969—\rthey made up a city of granite mills\rby a slate & blue river. That town was my father’s \rlife, & still is. If he felt cheated by it,\rby its fate for him,\rto bear that disappointment, he kept it secret. \r                                               That\rnight, when he stared deep into a drunk’s memory, \rhe frowned. He said nothing. He twisted on the stool, \rand ordered this guy a beer.\rWhatever my father & I have in common\ris mostly silence. And anger that keeps twisting \rback on itself, though not before it ruins,\roften, even something simple\ras a walk in the dunes at a warm beach.\rBut what we share too is a love so awkward\rthat it explains, with unreasoning perfection,\rwhy we still can’t speak\reasily to each other, about the past or anything else,\rand why I wake this far from the place where I grew up, \rwhile the wall above me claims now\rnothing has changed & all is different.\n	'1941':205 '1969':65,206 'air':122 'all-stat':136 'almost':151 'alway':152 'anger':286 'anyth':342 'ask':129 'awkward':321 'back':290 'ball':143 'ball-hawk':142 'bar':110 'basketbal':76 'beach':311 'beam':15 'bear':241 'beer':112,274 'bill':53 'blue':218 'breakfast':185 'call':125 'chamberlain':56 'championship':67 'chang':366 'chaser':113 'cheat':232 'citi':211 'claim':44,362 'color':103 'common':281 'contractor':170 'd':134 'day':163 'deep':253 'differ':369 'disappoint':243 'dog':27 'dog-ear':26 'drunk':124,256 'dune':307 'ear':28 'easili':334 'elbow':72 'els':343 'even':299 'ex':117 'ex-jock':116 'explain':324 'fall':1,108 'far':349 'fate':237 'father':94,224,277 'felt':231 'fight':168 'final':61 'fire':177 'follow':171,179 'forev':89 'frown':260 'fuzzi':102 'game':62,98 'get':40 'glossi':29 'granit':213 'grew':355 'gruff':155 'guard':139 'guy':272 'hard':69,202 'hawk':144 'haze':16 'hoars':115 'hous':167 'impati':158 'insid':88 'jam':107 'jock':118 'keep':288 'kept':245 'kid':182 'life':226 'like':42 'look':22 'love':319 'made':135,208 'magazin':30 'man':141 'mani':199 'memori':258 'men':70 'might':86 'mill':214 'mix':156 'moment':82,203 'most':283 'mother':188 'nba':66 'new':47 'next':51 'night':96,173,249 'noth':263,364 'ocher':10 'often':298 'one':57,59,83 'order':270 'pacer':145 'paint':164 'past':340 'perfect':327 'photo':31 'pine':14 'place':52,352 'play':99 'point':140 'rare':148 'ridg':13 'rift':120 'river':2,109,219 'ruin':297 'russel':54 'said':262 'saw':12 'saw-ridg':11 'seagram':111 'secret':247 'share':315 'shift':174 'shyness':160 'silenc':284 'simpl':301 'slate':217 'smoke':119 'snap':71 'snatch':73 'someth':146,300 'speak':333 'spoke':149 'stare':252 'state':138 'station':178 'stay':87,191 'still':227,330 'stone':201 'stone-hard':200 'stool':268 'streak':17 'suburban':165 'swarm':183 'tack':41 'taken':34 'televis':104 'though':293 'three':19 'tiger':127 'town':221 'tract':166 'tri':189 'twist':265,