1038	Writing	309		\nThe cursive crawl, the squared-off characters  these by themselves delight, even without  a meaning, in a foreign language, in Chinese, for instance, or when skaters curve  all day across the lake, scoring their white  records in ice. Being intelligible, these winding ways with their audacities  and delicate hesitations, they become  miraculous, so intimately, out there at the pen’s point or brush’s tip, do world  and spirit wed. The small bones of the wrist  balance against great skeletons of stars  exactly; the blind bat surveys his way  by echo alone. Still, the point of style  is character. The universe induces a different tremor in every hand, from the  check-forger’s to that of the Emperor Hui Tsung, who called his own calligraphy  the ‘Slender Gold.’ A nervous man writes nervously of a nervous world, and so on. Miraculous. It is as though the world were a great writing. Having said so much,  let us allow there is more to the world  than writing: continental faults are not  bare convoluted fissures in the brain.  Not only must the skaters soon go home;  also the hard inscription of their skates is scored across the open water, which long  remembers nothing, neither wind nor wake.\n	'across':32,197 'allow':161 'alon':94 'also':188 'audac':48 'balanc':79 'bare':174 'bat':88 'becom':53 'blind':87 'bone':75 'brain':179 'brush':65 'call':125 'calligraphi':128 'charact':9,101 'check':114 'check-forg':113 'chines':23 'continent':170 'convolut':175 'crawl':4 'cursiv':3 'curv':29 'day':31 'delic':50 'delight':13 'differ':106 'echo':93 'emperor':121 'even':14 'everi':109 'exact':85 'fault':171 'fissur':176 'foreign':20 'forger':115 'go':186 'gold':131 'great':81,153 'hand':110 'hard':190 'hesit':51 'home':187 'hui':122 'ice':40 'induc':104 'inscript':191 'instanc':25 'intellig':42 'intim':56 'lake':34 'languag':21 'let':159 'long':202 'man':134 'mean':17 'miracul':54,144 'much':158 'must':182 'neither':205 'nervous':133,136,139 'noth':204 'open':199 